\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constant Sheaf
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U):=E$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf (whose restriction maps being the identity map) called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf with value 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves are determined by their values on a basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If we know the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 of a sheaf on every element 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, then we can use the sheaf property to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(V)$
\end_inset

 on an arbitrary open set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We simply cover 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 by elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Here is a more systematic way of saying this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{F}(V) & =\left\{ (s_{U})_{U}\in\prod_{\substack{U\in\mathcal{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U)\mid\text{for }U'\subseteq U\text{ both in }\mathcal{B}\text{ we have }s_{U}|_{U'}=s_{U'}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{\substack{U\in\mathcal{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U).\label{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using this observation, we see that it suffices to define a sheaf on a basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 of open sets of the topology of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 as a full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

, then a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Every such presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the presheaf of bounded continuous functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is not a sheaf.
 Indeed, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=(i,i+2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=x|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and there is no bounded continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R};\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that for each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 of indices we are given isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ij}\colon\mathcal{F}_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\to\mathcal{F}_{i}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 satisfying for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k\in I$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cocycle condition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ik}=\varphi_{ij}\circ\varphi_{jk}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined up to unique isomorphism by these conditions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of collections of sections which are locally compatible:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})_{i\in I}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i}\cap U)\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}\cap U}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}\cap U}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} \label{eq:gluingsheaf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction maps are defined pointwise.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{V}=(s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap V})$
\end_inset

.
 The cocycle ensures that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gluingsheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gluingsheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has the slightly simpler description:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i,i'})_{i\in I}\in\mathcal{F}(U{}_{i'})$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(s_{i,i'})|_{U_{ii'j'}}=(s_{i,j'})|_{U_{ii'j'}}\label{eq:sheafsectjklfsdl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that there exists a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{U_{i'}}=(s_{i,i'})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafsectjklfsdl})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,i'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}=s_{i,j'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{ii'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf to obtain a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ii'}}=s_{i,i'}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain a unique sequence of sections 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{U_{i'}}=(s_{i,i'})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes uniqueness, so the only thing left to do is to check that
 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{iji'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{i}|_{U_{iji'}} & =s_{i,i'}|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j,i'})|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j,i'}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{iji'}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by the uniqueness part in the sheaf axiom (for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

), we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 as claimed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U)$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s)=(\varphi_{ji}(s|_{U_{j}\cap U}))_{j\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{j})_{j\in I}\in\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}(U)$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}((s_{j})_{j\in I})=s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s|_{V})=\psi_{i}(s)|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We repeat this construction for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 to get an isomorpism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 follows from a direct calculation: for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{j}(U_{ij})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij})(s) & =\psi_{i}(\varphi_{ij}(s))\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s)|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s))|_{U_{ijk}}){}_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s)|_{U_{ijk}})_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =\psi_{j}(s).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists a smallest neighborhood containing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can determine the sheaf completely by computing the values of the
 sheaf on these open sets.
 The problem of course is that the limit of the diagram which consists of
 all open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 may not exist, i.e.
 we may not have a smallest open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 However, colimits do exist in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, and there's nothing stopping us from looking at colimits in the diagram
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-images of neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, considered as a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{O}(X)\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{U}(x):=\{U\subseteq X\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\}
\]

\end_inset

be the set of open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, ordered by inclusion.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}(x)$
\end_inset

 as a full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 By restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(x)$
\end_inset

, we obtain a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{U}(x)\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}(x)$
\end_inset

 is filtered: for any two neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The colimit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}:=\mathrm{colim}_{U\in\mathbf{U}(x)}\mathcal{F}(U)
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
stalk 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 More concretely, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}=\left\{ (U,s)\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }s\in\mathcal{F}(U)\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},s_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},s_{2})$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}|_{V}=s_{2}|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 will be denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x}$
\end_inset

, or even more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mapsto[s_{x}]$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
germs
\series default
.

\series bold
 
\series default
If we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without first without specifying what the open neighboorhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is, then it will be understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[U^{x},s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 is some open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U^{x})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then obtain an induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:=\mathrm{colim}_{U\in\mathbf{U}(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=[\varphi(s)]_{x}.
\]

\end_inset

This map is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 commutes with restriction maps.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves to the category of sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf of functions, one should think of the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 as the set of functions defined in some unspecified open neighborhood of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is any category in which filtered colimits exist (for instance the category
 of groups, of rings, of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, or 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras, etc...), then the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 and we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 to the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us make this more precise for a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of groups.
 The group law of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)\sim(W,s|_{W})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)\sim(W,t_{W})$
\end_inset

 and the product 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 is the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,(s|_{W})(t|_{W}))$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way addition and multiplication is defined on the stalk for
 a sheaf of rings.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\text{ }}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of real analytic functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n},p}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}$
\end_inset

 is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(p)(x_{i_{1}}-p_{i_{1}})\cdots(x_{i_{k}}-p{}_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Two real analytic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined in open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 agree on some open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 if and only if they have the same Taylor expansion around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a well-defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n},p}\to$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of continuous functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{ev}_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(e_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 We claim that this is the unique maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove this, we need to show that the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 denote the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;W}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Inded, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 By the very same argument as in the example above, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the stability of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 property under composition and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto1/x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Working With Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following result will be used very often.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.18}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be two morphisms of presheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are both sheaves, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are both sheaves, the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are equal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[U^{x},s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x}=[V^{x},t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 are two germs in at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi_{U^{x}}(s)]_{x}=[\varphi_{V^{x}}(t)]_{x}$
\end_inset

 which implies there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x}\subseteq U^{x}\cap V^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{W^{x}}(s|_{W^{x}})=\varphi_{W^{x}}(t|_{W^{x}})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{W^{x}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{W^{x}}=t|_{W^{x}}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are two sections in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\varphi_{U}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $s=t$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 .
 By 1, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x}=[U,t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, there exists a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 By 1, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be a section in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, and so there exists a germ 
\begin_inset Formula $[s^{x}]_{x}=[U^{x},s^{x}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s^{x}]_{x})=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 with a smaller open set if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in U$
\end_inset

, denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{xy}=U^{x}\cap U^{y}$
\end_inset

 and observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}) & =\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =(t|_{U^{x}})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =t|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =(t|_{U^{y}})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{y}}(s^{y})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}=s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this implies there exists a unique section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=s^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

, then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be a section in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}(s)=\psi_{x}(s)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, we see that there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\psi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\psi_{U}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We call a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves 
\series bold
injective 
\series default
(respectively 
\series bold
surjective
\series default
, respectively 
\series bold
bijective
\series default
) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of sheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 there exist an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) and sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U_{i}}(s_{i})=t|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, if locally we can find a preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 But the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 does not imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in the proof above we needed injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 in order to patch up the various local sections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similary, as we defined the notions of injectivity or surjectivity 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stalkwise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we also define the notion of an exact sequence of sheaves of groups 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stalkwise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] & 
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi "]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{H} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

of homomorphisms of sheaves of groups is called 
\series bold
exact 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the induced sequence of stalks 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F}_x 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _x "] & 
\backslash
mathcal{G}_x 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _x"]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{H}_x 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is an exact sequence of groups.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of holomorphic functions on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 For every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{U}(f)=f'$
\end_inset

 be the derivative.
 .
 We obtain a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}$
\end_inset

 is surjective because locally every holomorphic function has a primitive.
 On the other hand, there exists open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 which have no primitive on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, take 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{C}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=1/z$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a primitive of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 be the path defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=e^{2\pi it}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =F(1)-F(1)\\
 & =F(\gamma(1))-F(\gamma(0))\\
 & =\int_{\gamma}f(z)\mathrm{d}z\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}f(\gamma(t))\gamma'(t)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{1}{e^{2\pi it}}2\pi i\cdot e^{2\pi it}\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}2\pi i\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =2\pi i,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is obviously a contradiction.
 The issue here comes from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)\cong\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental group of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, by complex analysis we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if every connected component of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is simply connected (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)=0)$
\end_inset

.
 The sufficiency of this condition will also be an immediate application
 of cohomologial methods developed later.
 We obtain an exact sequence of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathbb{C}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota "]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
mathrm{D}"]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 denotes the sheaf of locally constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{U}$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be sheaves on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) if and only
 if its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{U_{i}}\colon\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}\to\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 to morphisms of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 because these notions are defined via the stalks.
 But note that the existence of the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is crucial.
 There exists sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are not isomorphic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheafification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a functorial way to attach to a presheaf a sheaf:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propsheafification}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\widetilde{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}\colon\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves, such that the following holds: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves, then there exists a unique morphism of sheaves
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}':\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is unique up to unique isomorphism.
 Moreover, the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

, the map of stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}:\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and every morphism of presheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\mathcal{\widetilde{F}\to\widetilde{G}}$
\end_inset

 making the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramsheafification}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
varphi ", swap] & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi }"]  
\backslash

\backslash
  
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{G}} "]  & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a functor from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the category of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is called the sheaf associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 or the 
\series bold
sheafification 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 which we call the 
\series bold
sheafification 
\series default
functor.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the families of elements in the stalks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, which locally give rise to sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U) & :=\left\{ ([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}\Biggm|\begin{array}{c}
\text{for all }x_{0}\in U\text{ there exists an open neighborhood }U_{0}\subseteq U\text{ of }x_{0}\\
\text{and an }s_{0}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{0})\text{ such that }[s^{x}]_{x}=[U_{0},s_{0}]_{x}\text{ for all }x\in U_{0}
\end{array}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is another open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

, then we define the restriction map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{res}_{V}^{U}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(V)$
\end_inset

 pointwise, that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\mid_{V}=([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in V}.
\]

\end_inset

Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a sheaf.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}])_{x\in U_{i}}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U_{i}}|_{U_{ij}}=([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U_{ij}}=([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U_{j}}|_{U_{ij}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is the unique element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}|_{U_{i}}=([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the same proof also shows that presheaf given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U\mapsto\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}\colon\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}(s)=([s]_{x})_{x\in U}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 then the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}([s]_{x_{0}})=[([s]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x_{0}}\in\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we prove the two properties stated in the proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 First we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x_{0}}=[U,s]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x_{0}}=[V,t]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be two germs in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[([s]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}=[([t]_{x})_{x\in V})]_{x_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset

Then there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $([s]_{x})_{x\in W}=([t]_{x})_{x\in W}$
\end_inset

, or in other words, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x_{0}}=[t]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, using the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

, we can find a better representative for this germ: choose an open neighborhood
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and choose a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s^{x}]_{x}=[s_{0}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $[([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}=[([s_{0}]_{x})_{x\in U_{0}})]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}([s_{0}]_{x_{0}})=[([s_{0}]_{x})_{x\in U_{0}})]_{x_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\left(([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\right)=([\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})]_{x})_{x\in U}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that this gives rise a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves.
 Furthermore, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}(s) & =\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\left(([s]_{x})_{x\in U}\right)\\
 & =([\varphi_{U}(x)]_{x})_{x\in U}\\
 & =\iota_{\mathcal{G},U}(\varphi_{U}(s))\\
 & =\iota_{\mathcal{G},U}\varphi_{U}(s).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\varphi$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 makes the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagramsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism making the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagramsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is another morphism making the diagram commute, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\varphi=\widetilde{\varphi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}_{x}\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}=\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}=\widetilde{\psi}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}=\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we assume in addition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\colon\mathcal{G}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, which is bijective on stalks, is an isomorphism by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus we can define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}^{-1}\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and it is easily seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is a formal consequence from the universal mapping property.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmahomshpsh}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\mathcal{G})\longleftrightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}(X)}(\mathcal{F},\mathcal{G})
\]

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the sheafification functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 is the left adjoint to the forgetful functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the sheafification functor preserves all colimits whereas
 the forgetful functor preserves all limits.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\colon\widetilde{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then we 
\emph on
define 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Functoriality in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is an easy exercise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheafification of a presheaf of functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Define a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}(U)=\left\{ g\colon U\to E\mid\text{there exists an open covering }\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}\text{ of }U\text{ such that }g|_{U_{i}}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})\text{ for all }i\in I\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the restriction maps of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 being the usual ones.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $([U^{x},f^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 together with a section 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(V^{x})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[f^{y}]_{y}=[g^{x}]_{y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x,y}\subseteq U^{y}\cap V^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{y}|_{W^{x,y}}=g^{x}|_{W^{x,y}}$
\end_inset

.
 Define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon U\to E$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=g^{x}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is independent of our choice of the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(W^{x,y},V^{x},g^{x})$
\end_inset

 for if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{W}^{x,y},\widetilde{V}^{x},\widetilde{g}^{x})$
\end_inset

 were another such triple, then we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}^{x}(x)=f^{x}(x)=g^{x}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W^{x,y}\}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{W^{x,y}}=g^{x}|_{W^{x,y}}$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(z) & =g^{z}(z)\\
 & =f^{z}(z)\\
 & =g^{x}(z)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in W^{x,y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{W^{x,y}}=f^{y}|_{W^{x,y}}\in\mathcal{F}(W^{x,y})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we obtain map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $([f^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\mapsto g$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that this map induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\cong\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the constant presheaf with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 to be the sheaf of locally constant functions with value 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{X}(U)=\{f\colon U\to E\mid f\text{ is locally constant}\}.
\]

\end_inset

for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This is the sheafification of the presheaf of constant functions with values
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf 
\series default
with values in
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves and Etale Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bundles 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{samepage}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{slice category}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}/c$
\end_inset

 of a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 over an object 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the category whose objects are morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:d\to c$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $f:d\to c$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f':d'\to c$
\end_inset

 are the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $g:d\to d'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\circ g=f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

