\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation maps are surjective.
 Hence there exists a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 making the lower rectangle commutative if and only if one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{f(x)}))\subseteq\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 But this latter condition is satisfied because 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is local by 1.
 Moreover, as a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\text{id}_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we find 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{V}^{\flat}(t)(x)=t(f(x))$
\end_inset

, which shows 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is an isomorphism in the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves of rings.
 We claim that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}=\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}\circ f_{x}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}$
\end_inset

 is the isomorphism constructed in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propdirectstalk})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space, which we usually denote simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Such a locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space is called an 
\series bold
open subspace 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 There is an 
\series bold
inclusion morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, where the continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to X$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is given by the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')\to i_{*}(\mathcal{O}_{X|U})(U')=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap U')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\#}:i^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 is the identity.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the identity for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U}:U\to Y$
\end_inset

 the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ i$
\end_inset

 of morphisms of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $j:(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\to(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is called an 
\series bold
open embedding 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=j(Z)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\cong(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is called a 
\series bold
local isomorphism 
\series default
if there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}:U_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an open embedding for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In other words, a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local isomorphism if there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 an open subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorpism 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is a local isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}:\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(X_{i},\mathcal{F}_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of ringed spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i,j}:X_{i,j}\to X_{j,i}$
\end_inset

 be homeomorphisms for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
  Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X:=\coprod_{i\in I}X_{i}/\sim
\]

\end_inset

where if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim\varphi_{i,j}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 glue to a unique sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}})$
\end_inset

 be locally ringed spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1,2}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2,1}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(X_{1,2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}|X_{1,2}})\to(X_{2,1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}|X_{2,1}})$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of locally ringed spaces.
 Then we can define a locally ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 via the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a set, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\coprod X_{2}$
\end_inset

 modulo the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a topological space, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the so-called 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 induced by the above equivalence relation, i.e.
 we say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{1}\subseteq U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{2}\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both open, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=i_{1}(X_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=i_{2}(X_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}:X_{1}\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{2}:X_{2}\to X$
\end_inset

 being the obvious inclusion maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a ringed space, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{(s_{1},s_{2})\mid s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }f^{*}(s_{2})|{}_{U\cap X_{2,1}}=s_{1}|{}_{U\cap X_{1,2}})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Differential Geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Euclidean Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the prototype of all manifolds.
 Not only is it the simplest, but locally every manifold looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A good understanding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is essential in generalizing differential and integral calculus to a manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be a nonnegative integer and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if its partial derivatives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\partial_{x_{i_{2}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{j}}}f
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
of all orders 
\begin_inset Formula $j\leq k$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if all of its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 A similar defintion holds for a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We treat the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as synonymous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The polynomial, sine, cosine, and exponential functions on the real line
 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{3}x^{-2/3} & \mbox{for }x\neq0\\
\mbox{undefined} & \mbox{for }x=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid x\neq0\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt=\int_{0}^{x}t^{1/3}dt=\frac{3}{4}x^{4/3}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)=f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way one can construct a function that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k+1}$
\end_inset

 at a given point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth and even bijective with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is not smooth, as shown above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuity of a function can often be seen by inspection, but the smoothness
 of a function always requires a formula.
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{5/3}$
\end_inset

 looks perfectly smooth, but it is in fact not smooth at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, since its second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $y''=(10/9)x^{-1/3}$
\end_inset

 is not defined there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the norm function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We will do this in detail.
 First we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)=\frac{x_{n}}{\|x\|}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x_{n}}^{k+1}\left(\|x\|\right) & =\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\frac{f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}+\frac{(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k+1}}\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(x)\left(x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}\right)+(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2n+1}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes our claim.
 Now given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{1}}^{k_{1}}\cdots\partial_{x_{n}}^{k_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)/\|x\|^{2(k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n})-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial (just use the same induction proof).
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, we see that the norm function is smooth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be smooth.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will only sketch the proof here.
 By the chain rule, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}(g\circ f)=(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}f
\]

\end_inset

By the product rule we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}(g\circ f)=(g''\circ f)\cdot(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{2}+(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}(g\circ f)=(g'''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{3}+3(g''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f)+(g'\circ f)\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}f.
\]

\end_inset

More generally, we will have a pattern which involves stirling numbers.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
real-analytic
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 it is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})+\frac{1}{2!}\sum_{i,j}\partial_{x_{i}}\partial_{x_{j}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})(x_{j}-p_{j})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(p)(x_{i_{1}}-p_{i_{1}})\cdots(x_{i_{k}}-p_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A real-analytic function is necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, because as one learns in real analysis, a convergent power series can
 be differentiated term by term in its region of convergence.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\sin x=x-\frac{1}{3!}x^{3}+\frac{1}{5!}x^{5}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then term-by-term differentiation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\cos x=1-\frac{1}{2!}x^{2}-\frac{1}{4!}x^{4}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The following example shows that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be real-analytic.
 The idea is to construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 whose graph, though not horizontal, is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the sense that all of its derivatives vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{smoothnotanalytic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function very flat at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)=e^{-1/x}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $L(n,i)$
\end_inset

 are the Lah numbers.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 are well defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to0$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 much faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

).
 So this function is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the Taylor series of this function at the origin is
 identically zero in any neighborhood of the origin since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}f}{dx^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 cannot be equal to its Taylor series and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is not real-analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Taylor's Theorem with Remainder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Although a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be equal to its Taylor series, there is a Taylor's theorem
 with remainder for 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions that is often good enough for our purposes.
 We say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
star-shaped
\series default
 with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Taylor's theorem with remainder).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 star-shaped with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x),\dots,g_{n}(x)\in C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\qquad g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea behind this proof is to differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 and then integerate it.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 the line segment 
\begin_inset Formula $p+t(x-p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 By the chain rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{df}{dt}(p+t(x-p)) & =\frac{df}{dt}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}),\dots,p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}))+\cdots+(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we integrate both sides with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(p+t(x-p))|_{0}^{1}=\sum(x_{i}-p_{i})\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt\label{eq:inteq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to apply this proof to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(x) & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(tx)dt\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{-e^{-1/tx}}{tx^{2}}dt\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/tx}}{x}|_{0}^{1}\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(0)+x\left(\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In elementary calculus we normally represent a vector at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 algebraically as a column of numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
v_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or geometrically as an arrow emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is tangent to a surface in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 if it lies in the tangent plane at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Such a definition of a tangent vector to a surface presupposes that the
 surface is embedded in a Euclidean space, and so would not apply to the
 projective plane, for example, which does not sit inside an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in any natural way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Directional Derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point with direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The line through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be parametized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell:=(\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{n}):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(t):=p+tv=(p_{1}+tv_{1},\dots,p_{i}+tv_{i},\dots,p_{n}+tv_{n})=:(\ell_{1}(t),\dots,\ell_{i}(t),\dots,\ell_{n}(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
directional derivative
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & :=\lim_{t\to0}\left(\frac{f(\ell(t))-f(p)}{t}\right)\\
 & =\partial_{t}f(\ell(t))|_{t=0}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\partial_{x_{i}}f(\ell(0))\cdot\partial_{t}\ell_{i}(0)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

, it is understood that the partial derivatives are to be evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a number, not a function.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{v}=\sum v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for the map that sends a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the number 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation we often omit the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is clear from the context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Germs of Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 We introduce a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that this is an equivalence relation by showing it
 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What happens if we weaken the relation a bit? Say 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we no longer have an equivalence relation.
 The reason is because this relation is not transitive: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})\sim(f_{3},U_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

, but this merely implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{1-x}
\]

\end_inset

with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=1+x+x^{2}+x^{3}+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

with domain the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

 have the same germ at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The addition and multiplication of functions induce corresponding operations
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 making it into an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two representatives.
 Then multiplication is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})\cdot(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

We need to check that this is well-defined, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}',U_{1}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}',U_{2}')$
\end_inset

 be two different represenatives respectively.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}=f_{1}'\text{ on }W_{1}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{1}'\text{ and }f_{2}=f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{2}\subset U_{2}\cap U_{2}'
\]

\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}f_{2}=f_{1}'f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{1}\cap W_{2}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{2},
\]

\end_inset

and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2})\sim(f_{1}'f_{2}',U_{1}\cap U_{2})
\]

\end_inset

and hence this is well-defined.
 Similarly, addition is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})+(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}+f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This example requires some knowledge of Algebraic Geometry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set over an algebraically closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=A(X)$
\end_inset

 be its coordinate ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be the maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 given by the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

 which vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There are two equivalent ways to define the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 are equivalence classes of elements of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 if there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(g_{2}f_{1}-g_{1}f_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The other way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the ring of all germs of polynomial functions defined on a neighborhood
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polynomial function defined on a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 here as being the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f/g,D(g))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all points such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Two such polynomial functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}/g_{1},D(g_{1}))$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}/g_{2},D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

) represent the same germ if they agree on some small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A small open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the Zariski topology is simply something of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 does not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)\cap D(g_{1})\cap D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Another way of saying this is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}h(f_{1}/g_{1}-f_{2}/g_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; this matches precisely the criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be equal in the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivations at a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 gives a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed we just need to check that it is well-defined: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

 for some open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{f(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{g(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\partial_{x_{i}}g(p).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, which implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}g(p)\\
 & =D_{v}g.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined map.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear and satisfies the Leibniz rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{v}(fg)=(D_{v}f)g(p)+f(p)D_{v}g,\label{eq:leibnizrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

precisely because the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

 have these properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, any linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series default
or a 
\series bold
point-derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the set of all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 This set is in fact a real vector space, since the sum of two derivations
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a scalar multiplication of a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are again derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus far, we know that directional derivatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

where a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the point-derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is clearly linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a linear map of vector spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaconstantfunctions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a point-derivation of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=0$
\end_inset

 for any constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linearity, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=cD(1)$
\end_inset

, so it suffices to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By the the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(1)=D(1\cdot1)=D(1)\cdot1+1\cdot D(1)=2D(1).
\]

\end_inset

Substracting 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)$
\end_inset

 from both sides gives 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Kronecker delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a useful notation that we frequently call upon: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j.\\
0 & \text{if }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 defined above is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove injectivity, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 to the coordinate function 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =D_{v}x_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{i}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}x_{j}\mid_{p}\\
 & =v_{j}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove surjectivity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,V)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Making 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 smaller if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open ball, hence star-shaped.
 By Taylor's theorem with remainder, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to both sides and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(p)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p_{i})=0$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconstantfunctions})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we get by the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Df & =D(f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x))\\
 & =D(f(p))+\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(p)+(p_{i}-p_{i})Dg_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i})-D(p_{i}))g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(Dx_{1},\dots,Dx_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vector Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 has basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}\}$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}(p),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}(p)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are now functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if the coefficient functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=\frac{-y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{x}+\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=x\partial_{x}-y\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is commonly denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplication of vector fields by functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is defined pointwise:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f\vec{v})(p)=f(p)\vec{v}(p).
\]

\end_inset

Clearly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}f\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector fields on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vec}(U)$
\end_inset

, is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Fields as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we define a new function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\vec{v}(p)f
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 gives rise to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{\infty}(U)\to C^{\infty}(U),\qquad f\mapsto\vec{v}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Leibniz rule for a vector field) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(fg)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)(fg)=\vec{v}(p)(f)\cdot g(p)+f(p)\cdot\vec{v}(p)(g),
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 varies over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this becomes an inequality of functions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an algebra over a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, a 
\series bold
derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:A\to A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(ab)=(Da)b+a(Db),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition and scalar multiplication and forms a vector space,
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Der}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 As noted above, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a derivation of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore have a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:\text{Vec}(U)\to\text{Der}(C^{\infty}(U)),\qquad\vec{v}\mapsto(f\mapsto\vec{v}f).
\]

\end_inset

Just as the tangent vectors at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the point-derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, so the vector fields on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the derivations of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Exterior Algebra of Multicovectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The basic principle of manifold theory is the linearization principle, according
 to which every manifold can be locally approximated by its tangent space
 at a point, a linear object.
 In this way linear algebra enters into manifold theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Instead of working with tangent vectors, it turns out to be more fruitful
 to adopt the dual point of view and work with linear functions on a tangent
 space.
 After all, there is only so much that one can do with tangent vectors,
 which are essentially arrows, but functions, far more flexible, can be
 added, multiplied, and composed with other maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dual Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 the vector space of all linear maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:V\to W$
\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\series bold
dual space
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to be the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
covectors
\series default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
covectors 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 can be uniquely expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 be the linear function that picks out the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}(v)=v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{e}_{i}(e_{j})=\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{for }i=j,\\
0 & \mbox{for }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 span 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(v) & =\ell\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\underline{e}_{i}(v)\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}(v)\\
 & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\right)(v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\in\mbox{Span}(\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Next we show the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}\underline{e}_{i}=0,\label{eq:linearindependence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 By applying 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:linearindependence})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
dual basis 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 is a hyperplane in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be its dual basis.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in terms of the dual basis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\underline{e}_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}a_{i}=0.$
\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ker}(\ell)=V\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{i}\right)=\left\{ (x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\mid\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right)=n-k.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 We may assume that we are working in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}=\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right) & =\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}V\left(X_{i}\right)\right)\\
 & =\text{dim}\left(V\left(X_{1},\dots,X_{k}\right)\right)\\
 & =n-k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The converse is trivial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential Forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
cotangent space 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}))^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 In parallel with the definition of a vector field, a 
\series bold
covector field 
\series default
or 
\series bold
differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\series default
on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega:U\to\bigcup_{p\in U}T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),\qquad p\mapsto\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call a differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\series bold
-form 
\series default
for short.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jacobian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
Jacobian 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p):=\begin{pmatrix}(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{1})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{1})(p)\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{m})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{m})(p)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian satisfies the following property: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\|f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon)\|}{\|\varepsilon\|}\to0
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 One can view the Jacobian as a smooth linear map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)=(J(f)(p)_{1},\dots,J(f)(p)_{m}):\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m},
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f)(p)_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}(\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i})(p)x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to itself and the Jacobian matrix is a square matrix.
 In particular, we can compute its determinant, known as the 
\series bold
Jacobian determinant
\series default
.
 The Jacobian determinant at a given point gives important information about
 the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near that point.
 For instance, the inverse function theorem tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is invertible near a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the Jacobian determinant is non-zero.
 Furthermore, if the Jacobian determinant at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 preserves orientation near 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid xy\in(-\pi/2,\pi/2)\text{ and }x+y\in(0,\infty)\}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=\tan(xy)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=\ln(x+y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in U$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}y_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0}) & x_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})\\
\frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}} & \frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian determinant is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{det}\left(J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})\right)=\frac{(y_{0}-x_{0})\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})}{x_{0}+y_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=x^{2}+xy+y$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}+y_{0}\\
x_{0}+1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})\\
 & =x_{0}^{2}+x_{0}y_{0}+y_{0}+(2x_{0}+y_{0})\varepsilon_{1}+(x_{0}+1)\varepsilon_{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=x^{2}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=y^{2}+x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}y_{0} & x_{0}^{2}\\
1 & 2y_{0}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =((x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}),(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}^{2})+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1}))\\
 & =(x_{0}^{2}y_{0},y_{0}^{2}+x_{0})+(2x_{0}y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}+x_{0}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{1}+2y_{0}\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\subset\mathbb{R}^{m}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p+\varepsilon)=f(p)+J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon)+\psi(\varepsilon),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\psi(\varepsilon)\|/\|\varepsilon\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\varepsilon):=f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We first recall a few definitions from point-set topology.
 A topological space is 
\series bold
second countable
\series default
 if it has a countable basis.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is any open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Hausdorff
\series default
 if for every pair of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

, there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 An 
\series bold
open cover
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 whose union 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The Hausdorff condition and second countability are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hereditary properties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; they are inherited by subspaces: a subspace of a Hausdorff space is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is second countable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is second countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, choose a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'=U\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighboorhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'=V\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\cap V'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}'\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}'=B_{i}\cap M'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that there is a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
chart
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate neighborhood
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate open set
\series default
, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate map
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate system on 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
centered
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart on the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\phi|_{V})$
\end_inset

 is a chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi|_{V}:V\to\phi(V)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
topological manifold
\series default
 is a Hausdorff, second countable, locally Euclidean space.
 It is said to be of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if it is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is covered by a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map.
 It is the prime example of a topological manifold.
 Every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is also a topological manifold, with chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,1_{U})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cusp).
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a topological manifold.
 By virtue of being a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it is Hausdorff and second countable.
 It is locally Euclidean because it is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,x^{2/3})\mapsto x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=5, xmin=-5, ymax=5, ymin=-5, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({x^3},{4*x^2});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cross).
 The cross can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(r,0)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}\cup\{(0,r)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We show that the cross in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with the subspace topology is not locally Euclidean at the intersection
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(0,0)$
\end_inset

, and so cannot be a manifold.
 Suppose the cross is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 homeomorphic to an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=B_{\varepsilon}(0)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to B$
\end_inset

 restricts to a homemorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}\to B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is either connected if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 or has two connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 has four connected components, there can be no homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradiction proves that the cross is not locally Euclidean at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1/2]
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=1, xmin=-1, ymax=1, ymin=-1, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({0},{x});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({x},{0});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compatible Charts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi:V\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 are two charts of a topological manifold.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the image 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 will also be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi:V\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 of a topological manifold are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
compatible
\series default
 if the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\psi^{-1}:\psi(U\cap V)\to\phi(U\cap V)\qquad\psi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap V)\to\psi(U\cap V)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 These two maps are called the 
\series bold
transition functions
\series default
 between the charts.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is empty, then the two charts are automatically 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible.
 To simplify this notation, we will sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We will also sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}=\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are interested only in 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts, we often omit mention of 
\begin_inset Formula $"C^{\infty}"$
\end_inset

 and speak simply of compatible charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility is clearly reflexive and symmetric, but not necessarily transitiv
e.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the three coordinate functions are simultaneously defined only
 on the triple intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{123}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}=(\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{2})^{-1}\circ(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, but only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{123})$
\end_inset

, not necessarily on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13})$
\end_inset

.
 A priori we know nothing about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13}\setminus U_{123})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
atlas
\series default
 or simply an 
\series bold
atlas 
\series default
on a locally Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts that cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on a circle).
 The unit circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 may be described as the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0\leq t\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the two open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<\frac{1}{2}\}\qquad U_{2}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0<t<1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (-3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_1 $] (x) at (-2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_2 $] (x) at (2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:U_{i}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(e^{2\pi it})=t\qquad\phi_{2}(e^{2\pi it})=t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are branches of the complex log funciton 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/i)\log z$
\end_inset

 and are homeomorphisms onto their respective images.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}$
\end_inset

 consists of two connected components, the lower half 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the upper half 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<0\}\qquad B=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid0<t<\frac{1}{2}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{12})=\phi_{1}(A\cup B)=\phi_{1}(A)\cup\phi_{1}(B)=\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{2}(U_{12})=\phi_{2}(A\cup B)=\phi_{2}(A)\cup\phi_{2}(B)=\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transisition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{12})\to\phi_{2}(U_{12})$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t+1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t-1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts and form a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
compatible with an atlas
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 if it is compatible with all the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 of the atlas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{compatible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on a locally Euclidean space.
 If two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 are both compatible with the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, then they are compatible with each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}=(\sigma\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i}\circ\psi^{-1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})=\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

 and the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i}\circ\psi^{-1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 What the equality means in the proof above is that the two maps are equal
 on their common domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is said to be 
\series bold
maximal
\series default
 if it is not contained in a larger atlas; in other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 is any other atlas containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold is a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 together with a maximal atlas.
 The maximal atlas is also called a 
\series bold
differentiable structure
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold is said to have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if all of its connected components have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is also called a 
\series bold
curve
\series default
.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is a 
\series bold
surface
\series default
, and an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, to check that a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold, it is not necessary to exhibit a maximal atlas.
 The existence of any atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will do, because of the following proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is contained in a unique maximal atlas.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Adjoin to the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 all charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 that are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{compatible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 are compatible with one another.
 So the enlarged collection of charts is an atlas.
 Any chart compatible with the new atlas must be compatible with the original
 atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction belongs to the new atlas.
 This proves existence.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 is another maximal atlas containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

, then all the charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'\subset\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Since both are maximal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'=\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves uniqueness.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In summary, to show that a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold, it suffices to check that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff and second countable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From now on, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will mean a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 We use the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interchangeably.
 In the context of manifolds, we denote the standard coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{1},\dots,r^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is a chart of a manifold, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=r^{i}\circ\phi$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=(x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)=(U,x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{1}(p),\dots,x^{n}(p))$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1},\dots,x^{n}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
coordinates
\series default
 or 
\series bold
local coordinates 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 By abuse of notation, we sometimes omit the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So the notations 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

 stands alternately for local coordinates on the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological manifold can be endowed with different (non-compatible) different
iable structures.
 For instance, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We can give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{1})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to x$
\end_inset

.
 We can also give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These two charts are not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\circ\varphi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{\frac{1}{3}}$
\end_inset

, and this is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{\frac{1}{3}}\right)=\frac{1}{3}x^{-\frac{2}{3}}$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An Atlas For a Product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propproductofmanifolds}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}=\{(V_{j},\psi_{j})\mid j\in J\}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlases for the manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, respectively, then the collection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}=\{(U_{i}\times V_{j},\phi_{i}\times\psi_{j}:U_{i}\times V_{j}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}^{n})\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\}
\]

\end_inset

of charts is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m+n$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ U_{i}\times V_{j}\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\right\} $
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

, so we just need to show that any two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise compatible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1}\times V_{1},\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2}\times V_{2},\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}=\left(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}\right)\times\left(\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on their respective domains.
 The same proof shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible charts that cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propproductofmanifolds})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the infinite cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and the torus 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Euclidean space).
 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote coordinates functions and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote real numbers.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p)=a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(p)=a_{2}$
\end_inset

, and etc...
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The real half line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}:\{a\in\mathbb{R}\mid a>0\}$
\end_inset

 is also a smooth manifold, with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}_{>0},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{log}:\mathbb{R}_{>0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now consider the half-open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 Open sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 where and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq a<b<2\pi$
\end_inset

 form a basis for this topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Right-Half Infinite Strip and the Right-Half Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}_{>0}\times$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{-\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate this space below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [dashed, fill=gray!20] (-10,-2) rectangle (10,2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,2) -- (10,-2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-10,0.5) -- (10,0.5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=blue] (-10,0) -- (10,0);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=below:$ (1 
\backslash
text{,} 0 ) $] (a) at (-9,0) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=above:$ (r 
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
theta ) $] (a) at (0,0.5) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{R}_{>0}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the right-half plane.
 We illustrate this space below: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [dashed, fill=gray!20] (-10,-5) rectangle (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (-10,5) -- (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,5) -- (10,-5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,-5) -- (-10,-5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-10,0) -- (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=blue] (-10,0) -- (10,0);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=below:$ (1 
\backslash
text{,} 0 ) $] (a) at (-9,0) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=above:$ (a 
\backslash
text{,} b ) $] (a) at (0,2.5) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can give both 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the structure of a smooth manifold by simply using the identity charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r,\theta)=(\varphi_{1}(r,\theta),\varphi_{2}(r,\theta))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(r,\theta) & =r\sin\theta\\
\varphi_{2}(r,\theta) & =r\cos\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\theta)\in M$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(r,\theta)}(\varphi)=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\theta & r\cos\theta\\
\cos\theta & -r\sin\theta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:N\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(a,b)=(\psi_{1}(a,b),\psi_{2}(a,b))$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{1}(a,b) & =\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}\\
\psi_{2}(a,b) & =\arctan\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,b)}(\psi)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}}\begin{pmatrix}a & b\\
-b & a
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Manifolds of Dimension Zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Manifolds of dimension zero).
 In a manifold of dimension zero, every singleton subset is homeomorphic
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and so is open.
 Thus, a zero-dimensional manifold is a discrete set.
 By second countability, this discrete set must be countable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Graph of a Smooth Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Graph of a smooth function).
 For a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
graph
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the subset
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(f)=\{(p,f(p))\in A\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:\Gamma(f)\to U\qquad(p,f(p))\mapsto p
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1,f):U\to\Gamma(f)\qquad p\mapsto(p,f(p))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are continuous and inverse to each other, and so are homeomorphisms.
 The graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)$
\end_inset

 of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has an atlas with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma(f),\phi)$
\end_inset

, and is therefore a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 This shows that many familiar surfaces of calculus, for example an elliptic
 paraboloid or a hyperbolic paraboloid, are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplecirclestereographic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Circle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the unit circle centered at the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x^{2}+y^{2}=1\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall describe an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 using stereographic projection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=S^{1}\backslash\{(-1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which passes through the points 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation of this line is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=t(X+1).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and is not tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

, it must pass through a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is illustrated in the image below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-3,xmax=3,ymin=-3,ymax=3,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick=
\backslash
empty ,ytick=
\backslash
empty ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({0},{x}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({x},{2*x + 2}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$ (-1
\backslash
text{,}0) $] (a) at (axis cs:-1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(x
\backslash
text{,}y)$] (c) at (axis cs:-0.6,0.8) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(0
\backslash
text{,}t)$] (b) at (axis cs:0,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 lies on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and the unit circle, we get the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+y^{2}-1 & =0,\\
y-t(x+1) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the second relation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=t(x+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first relation, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{2}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}}=\frac{1-x}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, to get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\\
y & =\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}:U_{1}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset

This map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq-1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=S^{1}\backslash\{(1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Following the same line of reasoning as the paragraph above, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}:U_{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1-x}.
\]

\end_inset

Again, this map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}:=\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{12}(t) & =(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as a local coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 as global coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Projective Line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\in\mathbb{R},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in their domains.
 The inverse maps are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{0}^{-1}(t)=(1:t)\in U_{0}\qquad\phi_{1}^{-1}(t)=(t:1)\in U_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(t) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(t\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(t:1\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that this is the same transition map we calculated in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplecirclestereographic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplesphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sphere) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 the six charts corresponding to the six hemispheres - the front, rear,
 right , left, upper, and lower hemispheres
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{5}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c>0\}\qquad\phi_{5}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{6}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c<0\}\qquad\phi_{6}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{14}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0<a\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{4}(U_{14})=\{(a,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }a>0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a,c) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a,c)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right)\\
 & =\left(\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is easy to see that this is indeed a smooth map in its domain (since
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-c^{2}-a^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,c)}(\phi_{14})=\begin{pmatrix}\frac{a}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}} & \frac{c}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}}\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{45}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{45}(a,b) & =\phi_{4}\circ\phi_{5}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{4}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{nsphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Using stereographic projections (from the north pole and the south pole),
 we can define two charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the north pole and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{S}=(0,\dots,0,-1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the south pole.
 Define the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{N}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{S}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
stereographic projection 
\series default
from the north pole (resp.
 south pole), by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1-x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\quad\text{and}\quad\phi_{S}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1+x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

The inverse stereographic projections are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},-1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}$
\end_inset

 are two open subsets convering 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, both homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, it is easily checked that on the overlap, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}\cap U_{S}$
\end_inset

, the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}\circ\phi_{N}^{-1}=\phi_{N}\circ\phi_{S}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

that is, the inversion of center 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O}=(0,\dots,0)$
\end_inset

 and power 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, this map is smooth on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{O\}$
\end_inset

, so we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{N},\phi_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{S},\phi_{S})$
\end_inset

 form a smooth atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Real Projective Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleprojectiveplane}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Projective Plane) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective plane over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the three charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)=:(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)=:(c,d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=D(X_{2})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{2}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}\right)=:(e,f)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism is because given that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

, we use the equivalence relation to write the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are two real rumbers which uniquely determine the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 be the intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}:=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can also write this in terms of local coordinates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\{(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid c\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{01})\to\phi_{0}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 using the local coordinates.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{01}\left(c,d\right) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(c,d\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},\frac{d}{c}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}(c,d)=\frac{1}{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}(c,d)=\frac{d}{c}$
\end_inset

), the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{c}^{m}\partial_{d}^{n}\phi_{01}^{i}$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are rational functions (i.e.
 ratio of two polynomials) and are they are defined everywhere since 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

 in
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similarly, one can easily show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\phi_{10}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{a},\frac{b}{a}\right)\\
\phi_{20}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{b},\frac{a}{b}\right)\\
\phi_{02}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{f}{e},\frac{1}{e}\right)\\
\phi_{12}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{e}{f},\frac{1}{f}\right)\\
\phi_{21}(c,d) & =\left(\frac{c}{d},\frac{1}{d}\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

It is instructive to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{ji}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{jk}=\phi_{ik}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riemann Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riemann sphere) In this example we describe a 
\series bold
complex manifold
\series default
.
 A complex manifold is the complex analogue of a manifold, however in the
 complex manifold case, we require the transition maps to be holomorphic,
 and not just 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 (also known as the Riemann sphere).
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(z) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto\frac{1}{z}$
\end_inset

 is holomorphic in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobius Strip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to give this set the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 First we consider the set of all nonvertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonvertial is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid y=ax+b\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}:U_{v}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}\mapsto(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Next we consider the set of all nonhorizontal lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonhorizontal is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x=cy+d\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}:U_{h}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}\mapsto(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}\cup U_{h}=\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, we glue the topologies from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{h}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{vh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{hv}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{vh}(c,d) & =\varphi_{v}\circ\varphi_{h}^{-1}(c,d)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{c,d}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{hv}(a,b) & =\varphi_{h}\circ\varphi_{v}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{a,b}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, they look very similar to the transition maps for the projective
 plane, except they are twisted by a negative sign.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can also describe 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

: Any line in the euclidean plane is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by+c=0$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that these coefficients uniquely determine the line and they
 are homogeneous.
 Hence there is a well defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by mapping the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(ax+by+c)$
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[a:b:c]$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective, but not surjective.
 However if we remove the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[0:0:1]$
\end_inset

, then the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grassmannians
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-planes through the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane is a linear subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and has a basis consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 linearly independent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\dots,v_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore completely specified by an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=[a_{1}\cdots a_{k}]$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, where the 
\series bold
rank 
\series default
of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rk}A$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the number of linearly independent columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is called a 
\series bold
matrix representative 
\series default
of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Two bases 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\dots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 determine the same 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane if there is a change-of-basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g=[g_{ij}]\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{j}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}g_{ij}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 In matrix notation, this says 
\begin_inset Formula $B=Ag$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrices of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, topologized as a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 the equivalence relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\sim B\text{ if and only if there is a matrix }g\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})\text{ such that }B=Ag.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a bijection between 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 We give the Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 the quotient topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
real Grassmann manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined as the space of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspaces of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The topology in 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 may be described as induced by the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)\to\text{End}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 which assigns to a 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in G(n,k)$
\end_inset

, the orthogonal projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\to P$
\end_inset

 combined with the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $P\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $G(4,2)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}\sim\begin{pmatrix}c_{11} & c_{12}\\
c_{21} & c_{22}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}c_{11}a_{11}+c_{12}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}\\
c_{21}a_{11}+c_{22}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{11}c_{22}-c_{21}c_{12}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Smooth Maps on a Manifold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we've defined smooth manifolds, it is time to consider maps between
 them.
 Using coordinate charts, one can transfer the notion of smooth maps from
 Euclidean spaces to manifolds.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in an atlas, the smoothness of a map turns out
 to be independent of the choice of charts and is therefore well defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 or 
\series bold
smooth at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a function defined on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Observe that the definition of the smoothness of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is independent of the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, for if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any other chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ\psi^{-1}\mid_{\psi(U\cap V)}=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ(\phi\circ\psi^{-1}),
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Also observe that in the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not assumed to be continuous.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, being a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 in an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of continuous functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are only interested in functions that are smooth on an open set,
 there is no loss of generality in assuming at the onset that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 a real-valued function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\psi(V)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will prove the proposition as a cyclic chain of implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): This follows directly from the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function, since by (2) every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 has a coordinate neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in V$
\end_inset

.
 By the remark above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The smoothness conditions of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will be a recurrent motif: to prove the smoothness of an object, it is
 sufficient that a smoothness criterion hold on the charts of some atlas.
 Once the object is shown to be smooth, it then follows that the same smoothness
 criterion holds on 
\emph on
every 
\emph default
chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a map and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
pullback 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}h$
\end_inset

, is the composite function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\circ F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this terminology, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 if and only if its pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi^{-1})^{*}f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 of Euclidean space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be rotation counterclockwise by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi^{*}x & =(\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y\\
\phi^{*}y & =(\sin\theta)x+(\cos\theta)y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},e_{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $x(e_{1})=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi^{*}x)(a,b) & =x\left(\phi(a,b)\right)\\
 & =x\left(\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b,\sin\theta a+\cos\theta b\right)\\
 & =\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b\\
 & =((\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y)(a,b).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Maps Between Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We emphasize again that unless otherwise specified, by a manifold we always
 mean a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 We use the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interchangeably.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be manifolds of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 A continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a map from the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the definition, we needed 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 to be open so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps between manifolds are by definition continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In case 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{m},1_{\mathbb{R}^{m}})$
\end_inset

 as a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

 if and only if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, we recover the definition of a function being 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at a point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We show now that the definition of the smoothness of a map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 at a point is independent of the choice of charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

, there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in a differentiable structure, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on open subsets of Euclidean spaces.
 Hence, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}\mid_{\phi\left(F^{-1}(V\cap V_{\beta})\cap U\cap U_{\alpha}\right)}=(\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1})\circ(\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}),
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Notes_190117_135420_7a4_1.jpg
	lyxscale 20
	scale 20
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a map in terms of charts).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be smooth manifolds, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are atlases 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 By (2), 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 are charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap F^{-1}(V)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U\cap F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 was an arbitary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G:M\to P$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of manifolds, then the composite 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F:N\to P$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 be charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}=(\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1})\circ(\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of open subsets of Euclidean spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
diffeomorpism 
\series default
of manifolds is a bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the next two propositions, coordinate maps are diffeomorphisms,
 and conversely, every diffeomorphism of an open subset of a manifold with
 an open subset of a Euclidean space can serve as a coordinate map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then the coordinate map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, so it suffices to check that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are smooth.
 To test the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (U,\phi)\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (\phi(U),\text{id}_{\phi(U)})\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{\phi(U)}\circ\phi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.8})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To test smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to U$
\end_inset

, we use the same atlases as above.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\phi^{-1}\circ\text{id}_{\phi(U)}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:U\to F(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is a chart in the differentiable structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 in the maximal atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.10})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As composites of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps, both 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the maximal atlas.
 By the maximality of the atlas, the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is in the atlas.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Smoothness in Terms of Components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this subsection, we derive a criterion that reduces the smoothness of
 a map to the smoothness of real-valued functions on open sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a vector-valued function) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness in terms of components).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},\dots,F_{m}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Just as in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 case, we introduce an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be represent a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0}\cap U,\phi_{\mid U})$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(f\mid_{U_{0}\cap U},U_{0}\cap U)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may always assume that a germ can be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we obtain an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\phi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\phi^{-1},\phi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 Of course this map depends on our choice of chart.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 was another chart, then we'd obtain another isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\varphi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\varphi^{-1},\varphi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 We can relate these two isomorphisms via the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We describe the structure of a premanifold as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{M}(U):=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:\phi_{i}(U\cap U_{i})\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see that this is a premanifold, fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 open let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1}:\phi_{i_{0}}(U_{i_{0}}\cap U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{M}(U)$
\end_inset

 because the change of charts between 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-diffeomorphisms.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}=(f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i_{0}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 yields an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{M|U_{i_{0}}})\cong(Y_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{i_{0}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(M,\mathcal{O}_{M})$
\end_inset

 is a ringed space that is locally isomorphic to a manifold.
 Hence it is a premanifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:\mathbb{R}\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)=(\cos t,\sin t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}.$
\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas which consists of a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 we use the atlas which consists of the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{4},\phi_{4})$
\end_inset

 where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{13}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{24}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{23}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

.
 Let's compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\phi_{1}(F(t))\\
 & =(\phi_{1}((\cos t,\sin t))\\
 & =\sin t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{2}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\sin t\\
(\phi_{3}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t\\
(\phi_{4}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

These maps are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=(t^{2},t^{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a,b,c)=c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{6},\phi_{6})$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\circ\phi_{6}^{-1})(a,b) & =f\left(\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\right)\\
 & =f\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}-b^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us show that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 To avoid confusing functions with points, we will denote a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and use 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 to mean the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $x(a,b)=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(a,b)=b$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 restrict to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $i:S^{1}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $i(p)=(x(p),y(p))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and so the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{S^{1}}=f\circ i$
\end_inset

 with be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 too.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider first the function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We use the following atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, it is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, it suffices to check the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1}:\phi_{3}(U_{3})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1})(b)=x\left(\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq\pm1$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1-b^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{4}^{-1})(b)=x\left(-\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=-\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the four open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1},U_{2},U_{3},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, which cover 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is similar.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let's construct a smooth function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{16})=\{(b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid b^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }c<0\}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\phi_{6}(U_{16})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}<1\text{ and }0<a\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(b,c)=b^{2}+c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}^{*}(f):\phi_{6}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}(a,b) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}^{*}(f)(a,b) & =(f\circ\phi_{16})(a,b)\\
 & =f\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to the open unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 with inverse given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta^{-1}(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let us first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\beta(x)\| & =\sqrt{\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}+\cdots+\left(\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & <\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 This comes down to checking the component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are smooth:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}:=\beta_{i}(x).
\]

\end_inset

This follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is smooth follows by the same reasoning.
 Finally, checking that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\beta^{-1}(x))=x$
\end_inset

 is tedious but trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta(\beta^{-1}(x)) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\cdots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right)\\
 & =\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inverse Function Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally invertible 
\series default
or a 
\series bold
local diffeomorphism 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $F|_{U}:U\to F(U)$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},\dots,F_{n}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one would like to know whether they form a coordinate system, possibly
 on a smaller neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to whether 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(F_{1},\dots,F_{n}):N\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a local diffeomorphism at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse function theorem provides an answer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Inverse function theorem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Ler 
\begin_inset Formula $F:W\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map defined on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is locally invertible at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if and only if the Jacobian determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(J(F)_{p})$
\end_inset

 is not zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Inverse function theorem for manifolds).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tangent Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By definition, the 
\series bold
tangent space 
\series default
to a manifold at a point is the vector space of derivations at the point.
 A smooth map of manifolds induces a linear map, called its 
\series bold
differential
\series default
, of tangent spaces at corresponding points.
 In local coordinates, the differential is represented by the Jacobian matrix
 of partial derivatives of the map.
 In this sense, the differential of a map between manifolds is a generalization
 of the derivative of a map between Euclidean spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Tangent Space at a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Just as for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we define a 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be an equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions defined in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, two such functions being equivalent if they agree on some, possibly smaller,
 neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The set of germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 real-valued functions at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 The addition and multiplication of functions make 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 into a ring; which scalar multiplication by real numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 becomes an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Generalizing a derivation at a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we define a 
\series bold
derivation at a point 
\series default
in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, or a 
\series bold
point-derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

, to be a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(fg)=(Df)g(p)+f(p)Dg.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
tangent vector 
\series default
at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}+y^{3}+x+1:=t$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x_{0},y_{0})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{2}\to T_{f(p)}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by taking a derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f(p)}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{*}D)(g)=D(g\circ f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{3}-x:=t$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}\mapsto(3x_{0}^{2}-1)\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\mapsto\left(f_{1}(x,y),f_{2}(x,y)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1}(x,y) & =x\\
f_{2}(x,y) & =\frac{xy^{2}}{y^{2}+1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(x_{0},y_{0})}(f_{1},f_{2})=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
\frac{y_{0}^{2}}{y_{0}^{2}+1} & \frac{2x_{0}y_{0}}{(y_{0}^{2}+1)^{2}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2x_{0}y_{0}}{(y_{0}^{2}+1)^{2}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We describe 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 in another way.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the set of paths through 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}_{p}:=\{\gamma:(-a,a)\to M\mid\gamma\text{ is }C^{\infty}\text{ and }\gamma(0)=p\}.
\]

\end_inset

We define an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}$
\end_inset

 as follows: we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}\sim\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 if there exist a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'(0)=(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'(0).
\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 are paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is independent of the choice of chart.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is another chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi\circ\gamma_{1})' & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\gamma_{2})'
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The tangent space at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{p}M:=\mathcal{P}_{p}/\sim.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ \left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)\mid\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the cylinder.
 Define the two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M,\psi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M\cap\left\{ (\frac{-\pi}{,2},\frac{\pi}{2})\times(\frac{-\pi}{,2},\frac{\pi}{2})\times\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)=(\alpha,\beta)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\psi\left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)=(\cos\alpha,\beta).
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{1}(t)=(\cos(t^{2}),\sin(t^{2}),t)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\gamma_{2}(t)=(0,1,t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})(t)=(t^{2},t)\qquad\text{and}\qquad(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})(t)=\left(\frac{\pi}{2},t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'(0)=(0,1)=(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'(0)
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}\sim\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partial Derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 As a function into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 components 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1},\dots,\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=x_{i}\circ\phi$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
partial derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\series default
denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi_{i}}f$
\end_inset

, to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{\phi_{i}}\mid_{p}f:=(\partial_{\phi_{i}}f)(p):=\partial_{x_{i}}(f\circ\phi^{-1})(\phi(p)):=\partial_{x_{i}}\mid_{\phi(p)}(f\circ\phi^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the projective plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Use the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\{(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid a{}_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})=\left(\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}},\frac{a_{2}}{a_{0}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{1}(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2}) & =(x_{1}\circ\phi)(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})\\
 & =x_{1}(\phi(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2}))\\
 & =x_{1}\left(\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}},\frac{a_{2}}{a_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})=a_{2}/a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polar Coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following smooth map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\\
\theta & =\text{arctan}\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
dr & =\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dx+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dy\\
d\theta & =\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
rdrd\theta & =\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dx+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dy\right)\left(\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy\right)\\
 & =\left(xdx+ydy\right)\left(\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(xdx+ydy\right)\left(-ydx+xdy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(-xydxdx+x^{2}dxdy-y^{2}dydx+xydydy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(x^{2}dxdy-y^{2}dydx\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(x^{2}dxdy+y^{2}dxdy\right)\\
 & =\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dxdy\\
 & =dxdy.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we can integrate the Gaussian as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{\infty}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-(x^{2}+y^{2})}dxdx & =\int_{0}^{\pi/2}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-r^{2}}rdrd\theta.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse map is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =r\cos\theta\\
y & =r\sin\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Immersion, Embedding, Submersion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is called an
\series bold
 immersion 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}:T_{p}N\to T_{F(p)}M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
immersion 
\series default
if it is an immersion at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
submersion 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}:T_{p}N\to T_{F(p)}M$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
submersion 
\series default
if it is an submersion at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The prototype of an immersion is the inclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in a higher-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},0,\dots,0).
\]

\end_inset

The prototype of a submersion is the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 onto a lower-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(a_{1},\dots,a_{m},a_{m+1},\dots,a_{n})=(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to M$
\end_inset

 is both an immersion and submersion.
 This example shows in particular that a submersion need not be onto.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Critical Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
critical point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}$
\end_inset

 is not surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
critical value 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(q):=\{p\in N\mid F(p)=q\}$
\end_inset

 contains a critical point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Then the set of critical values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Measure Theory on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 be the Lebesgue measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(a,b)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(I)=b-a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are disjoint intervals, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(I\cup J)=\mu(I)+\mu(J)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, you can cover 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 by a union of intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\{I_{n}\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\bigcup_{n}I_{n}\right)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, define the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n}:=\left(\frac{-1}{4n},\frac{1}{4n}\right)\cup\left(1-\frac{1}{4n},1+\frac{1}{4n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a disjoint union of intervals which covers 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu(A_{n}) & =\frac{1}{4n}-\frac{-1}{4n}+1+\frac{1}{4n}-\left(1-\frac{1}{4n}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(A_{n})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ (x,x+\sin(x))\mid x\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the projection onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,x+\sin(x))\mapsto x+\sin(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A critical point is 
\series bold
degenerate 
\series default
if the associated Hessian matrix is 
\series bold
singular
\series default
 (i.e.
 has determinant equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ \left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)\mid\theta\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\left\{ \left(x,y,0\right)\mid x,y\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be the projection map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)\mapsto\left(\cos\theta,\theta,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(M,\psi_{M})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(N,\psi_{N})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{M}\left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)=\theta\qquad\text{and}\qquad\psi_{N}\left(x,y,0\right)=(x,y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\pi}{4},2+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)\in M$
\end_inset

? Then answer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}:=\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\right)
\]

\end_inset

 A critical point is 
\series bold
degenerate 
\series default
if the associated Hessian matrix is 
\series bold
singular 
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent Bundle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold.
 The 
\series bold
Tangent Bundle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TM:=\bigcup_{p\in M}T_{p}M.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}:=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then an atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}_{T}:=\{(U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{n},\phi_{i}\times\text{id})\}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, if we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}:=\phi_{i}\times\text{id}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}:U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{2n}$
\end_inset

 and we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n},y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The tangent bundle of the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to the cylinder.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There exist a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,v)\mapsto v$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default
is a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ\omega=\text{id}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Intuitively, a vector field is the data of a vector at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 comes with two gadgets.
 The first gadget is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
parameter 
\series default
flow and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The second gadget is called a 
\series bold
differential operator
\series default
 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 of a smooth manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the natural projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p,v)=p$
\end_inset

, makes 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 into a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
vector bundle 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, which we now define.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given any map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

, we call the inverse image 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(p):=\pi^{-1}(\{p\})$
\end_inset

 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
fiber 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The fiber at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For any two maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi':E'\to M$
\end_inset

 with the same target space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:E\to E'$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
fiber-preserving 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(E_{p})\subset E_{p}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, this says that the following diagram commutes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E 
\backslash
arrow[rr, "
\backslash
phi "] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
pi ", swap] && E'  
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
pi ' "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 &M 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A surjective smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds is said to be 
\series bold
locally trivial of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a vector space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, there are an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a fiber-preserving diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\pi^{-1}(U)\to U\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in U$
\end_inset

 the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\mid_{E_{q}}:E_{q}\to\{q\}\times\mathbb{R}^{r}
\]

\end_inset

is a vector space isomorphism.
 Such an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivializing open set 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivialization 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U,\phi)\}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U\}$
\end_inset

 and open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, is called a 
\series bold
local trivialization 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U\}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivializing open cover 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\series bold
vector bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

 consisting of manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and a surjective smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 that is locally trivial of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
total space 
\series default
of the vector bundle and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
base space
\series default
.
 By abuse of language, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Properly speaking, the tangent bundle of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(TM,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is the total space of the tangent bundle.
 In common usage, 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is often referred to as the tangent bundle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gluing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given two local trivializations 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:\pi^{-1}(U_{i})\to U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}:\pi^{-1}(U_{j})\to U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

, we obtain a smooth gluing map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}\to U_{i}\cap U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This map preserves images to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and hence it sends 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,v)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,g_{ji}(v))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix smoothly depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the gluing map is uniquely specified by a smooth map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{ji}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\to\text{GL}_{k}(\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset

These are called 
\series bold
transition functions 
\series default
of the bundle, and since they come from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, they clearly satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, as well as the cocycle condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{ij}g_{jk}g_{ki}=\text{id}\mid_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k}}\text{ }
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To build a vector bundle, choose an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 and form the pieces 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then glue these together on the double overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap U_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 via functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\to\text{GL}_{k}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as well as the cocycle condition, the resulting space has a vector bundle
 structure.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}\to M$
\end_inset

 be the projection to the first factor.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is a vector bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
product bundle 
\series default
of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The vector space structure on the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(p)=\{(p,v)\mid v\in\mathbb{R}^{r}\}$
\end_inset

 is the obvious one: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p,u)+(p,v)=(p,u+v)\text{ and }b\cdot(p,v)=(p,bv)\text{ for }b\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

A local trivialization on 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{M\times\mathbb{R}}:M\times\mathbb{R}\to M\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the infinite cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is the product bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 over the circle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{E}:E\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{F}:F\to N$
\end_inset

 be two vector bundles, possibly of different ranks.
 A 
\series bold
bundle map 
\series default
from 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a pair of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:E\to F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
widetilde{f} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
pi _{_E} ", swap] & F 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
pi _{_F} "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "f", swap]  & N 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is commutative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is linear one each fiber; i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:E_{p}\to F_{f(p)}$
\end_inset

 is a linear map of vector spaces for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collection of all vector bundles together with bundle maps between them
 forms a category.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds induces a bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:TN\to TM$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(p,v)=(f(p),f_{*}(v))\in\{f(p)\}\times T_{f(p)}M\subset TM
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}N$
\end_inset

.
 This gives rise to a covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 from the category of smooth manifolds and smooth maps to the category of
 vector bundles and bundle maps: to each manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we associate its tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, and to each 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds, we associate the bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f)=(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are two vector bundles over the same manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then a bundle map from 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a bundle map in which the base map is the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 For a fixed manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we can also consider the category of all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector bundles over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bundles maps over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In this category it makes sense to speak of an isomorphism of vector bundles
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Any vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to the product bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivial bundle
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left\{ (x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid\text{det}\begin{pmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{pmatrix}=0\right\} =\left\{ (x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x^{2}+\left(y-\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{4}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This can be realized as the circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 centered at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

 in the plane.
 There is natural vector bundle associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in M$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}:=\text{Ker}\left(\begin{smallmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}\left(\begin{smallmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{smallmatrix}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Smooth Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
section 
\series default
of a vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $s:M\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ s=1_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This condition means precisely that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 into the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a section is 
\series bold
smooth 
\series default
if it is smooth as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a function that assigns a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of the tangent bundle, a vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is simply a section of the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

 and the vector field is 
\series bold
smooth 
\series default
if it is smooth as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{(x,y)}=-y\partial_{x}+x\partial_{y}
\]

\end_inset

defines a smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Whitney Sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(E',M,\pi')$
\end_inset

 be two vector bundles.
 We can construct a new vector bundle called the 
\series bold
Whitney sum
\series default
, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi,\pi'):E\oplus E'\to M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E=L\oplus L'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 are line bundles.
 Then we can make a new bundle called 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Throughout this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 to be the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As every ring has a unique structure as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-algebra, we simply say (
\series bold
locally) ringed space 
\series default
instead of 
\series bold
(locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-ringed space
\series default
.
 Usually we will denote a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space by 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{X}^{\infty}(U):=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\text{ function}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Differential Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
cotangent space 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}M$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the dual space of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{p}^{*}M=(T_{p}M)^{\lor}=\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(T_{p}M,\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset

An element of the cotangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}M$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
covector 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a linear function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{p}:T_{p}M\to\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
covector field
\series default
, also called a 
\series bold
differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\series default
or more simply a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
form
\series default
, on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense it is dual to a vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, which assigns to each point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a tangent vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There are many reasons for the great utility of differential forms in manifold
 theory, among which is the fact that they can be pulled back under a map.
 This is in contrast to vector fields, which in general cannot be pushed
 forward under a map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Differential of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 real-valued function on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, its 
\series bold
differential 
\series default
is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(df)_{p}(X_{p})=X_{p}f.
\]

\end_inset

Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(df)_{p}$
\end_inset

 we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $df\mid_{p}$
\end_inset

 for the value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bump Functions and Partitions of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition of unity on a manifold is a collection of nonnegative functions
 that sum to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Usually one demands in addition that the partition of unity be 
\series bold
subordinate 
\series default
to an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 What this means is that the partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is indexed over the same set as the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the index 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity is one of the most technical tools in the theory of
 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds.
 It is the single feature that makes the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds so different from that of real-analytic or complex manifolds.
 In this section we construct 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump functions on any manifold and prove the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity on a compact manifold.
 The proof of the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity of a general manifold is more technical and is postponed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition of unity is used in two ways: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
to decompose a global object on a manifold into a locally finite sum of
 local objects on the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 of an open cover.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
to patch together local objects on the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 into a global object on the manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, a partition of unity serves as a bridge between global and local analysis
 on a manifold.
 This is useful because while there are always local coordinates on a manifold,
 there may be no global coordinates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Bump Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
support 
\series default
of a real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the closure in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of the subset on which 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}f:=\overline{f^{-1}(\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\})}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 By a 
\series bold
bump function at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
supported in
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we mean any continuous nonnegative function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The support of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-1,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tan(\pi x/2)$
\end_inset

, is the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

, and not the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

, because the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\})$
\end_inset

 is taken in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

 and not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{smoothnotanalytic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to build a smooth bump function function from 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The main challenge in building a smooth bump function from 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is to construct a smooth version of a step function.
 We seek 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 by dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 by a positive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

, for the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)/\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 will be zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 should be a positive function that agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

, for then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)/\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 will be identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 The simplest way to construct such an 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 is to add to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 a nonnegative function that vanishes for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 One such nonnegative function is 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1-t)$
\end_inset

.
 This suggests that we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)=f(t)+f(1-t)$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{f(t)}{f(t)+f(1-t)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given two positive real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

, we make a linear change of variables to map 
\begin_inset Formula $[a^{2},b^{2}]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\mapsto\left(\frac{x-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right):
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x)=g\left(\frac{x-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 step function such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }x\leq a^{2}\\
1 & \text{if }x\ge b^{2}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Now replace 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 to make the function symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)=h(x^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(x)=1-k(x)=1-g\left(\frac{x^{2}-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that is identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-a,a]$
\end_inset

 and has support in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-b,b]$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x-q)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to extend the construction of a bump function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on the closed balled 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B_{a}(\mathbf{0})}$
\end_inset

 and has support in the closed ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B_{b}(\mathbf{0})}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(x)=\rho\left(\|x\|\right)=1-g\left(\frac{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

As a composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, take 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(x-q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extending 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Bump Functions to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose we have manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(U_{i})\cong B_{b}(\phi(q))$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

, and choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}\subseteq U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(V_{i})\cong B_{a}(\phi(q))$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

.
 We've shown now to construct a bump function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(q)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{a}(\phi_{i}(q))$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=0$
\end_inset

 outside 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{b}(\phi_{i}(q))$
\end_inset

.
 Now we pull back 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to get a bump function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{i}^{*}\rho)(q')=\rho(\phi_{i}(q'))\text{ for all }q'\in U_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally we extend this function a bump function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\rho}(q')=\begin{cases}
(\phi_{i}^{*}\rho)(q') & \text{if }q'\in U_{i}\\
0 & \text{if }q'\notin U_{i}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Let us show that this function is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q'\in U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we simply choose the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widetilde{\rho}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})(x)=(\phi^{*}\rho)(\phi_{i}^{-1}(x))=\rho(x),
\]

\end_inset

shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q'\notin U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we choose a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{j},U_{j})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widetilde{\rho}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1})(x)=\widetilde{\rho}(\phi_{j}^{-1}(x))=0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 we constructed is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Extension of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 cannot be extended to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

; an example is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sec x$
\end_inset

 on the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi/2,\pi/2)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 However, if we require that the global function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 agree with the given function only on some neighborhood of a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 extension is possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 extension of a function) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function defined on a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in some possibly smaller neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 supported in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that is identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(q)=\begin{cases}
\rho(q)f(q) & \text{if }q\in U\\
0 & \text{if }q\notin U
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the product of two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin\text{supp}\rho$
\end_inset

, and so there is an open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin U$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This proposition says that the natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Thus, every germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 can be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,M)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partitions of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a finite open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
partition of unity subordinate to 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of nonnegative functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}:M\to\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=1.\label{eq:partitionofunity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an infinite set, for the sum in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:partitionofunity})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to make sense, we will impose a 
\series bold
local finiteness 
\series default
condition.
 A collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 of subsets of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
locally finite 
\series default
if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood that meets only finitely many of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is contained in only finitely many of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r,n}$
\end_inset

 be the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r-\frac{1}{n},r+\frac{1}{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{r,n}\mid r\in\mathbb{Q},\text{ }n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not locally finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
partition of unity 
\series default
on a manifold is a collection of nonnegative 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}:M\to\mathbb{R}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The collection of supports, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\text{supp}\rho\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, is locally finite, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we say that a partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
subordinate to the open cover 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the collection of supports, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\text{supp}\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, is locally finite, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 lies in only finitely many of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}(q)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the open intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,\infty)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{V}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth step function which is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,0)$
\end_inset

 and equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{U}=1-\rho_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{V}\subset V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{U}\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{U},\rho_{V}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity subordinate to the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U,V\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Existence of a Partition of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection we begin a proof of the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity on a manifold.
 Because the case of a compact manifold is somewhat easier and already has
 some of the features of the general case, for pedagogical reasons we give
 a separate proof for the compact case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma13.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\dots,\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 are real-valued funcitons on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}\right)\subset\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}\text{supp}\rho_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\text{supp}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}\text{supp}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a compact manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in M$
\end_inset

, find an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 from the given cover and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 supported in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}(q)>0$
\end_inset

, there is a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}>0$
\end_inset

.
 By the compactness of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W_{q}\mid q\in M\}$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcover, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W_{q_{1}},\dots,W_{q_{m}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q_{1}},\dots,\psi_{q_{m}}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding bump functions.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:=\sum_{j=1}^{m}\psi_{q_{j}}$
\end_inset

 is positive at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in W_{q_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{j}=\frac{\psi_{q_{j}}}{\psi},\quad j=1,\dots,m.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{m}\varphi_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{j}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q_{j}}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\varphi_{j}=\text{supp}\psi_{q_{j}}\subset U_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The next step is to make the index set of the partition of unity the same
 as that of the open cover.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)\in I$
\end_inset

 to be an index such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{\tau(j)}.
\]

\end_inset

We group the collection of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 into subcollections according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)$
\end_inset

 and define for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i}=\sum_{\tau(j)=i}\varphi_{j};
\]

\end_inset

if there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)=i$
\end_inset

, the sum is empty and we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=\sum_{i\in I}\sum_{\tau(j)=i}\varphi_{j}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}\varphi_{j}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma13.5})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset\bigcup_{\tau(j)=i}\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integration on Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Riemann Integral of a Function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
closed rectangle 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $R=[a_{1},b_{1}]\times\cdots\times[a_{n},b_{n}]$
\end_inset

 of closed intervals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},b_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:R\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded function defined on a closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{vol}(R)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of the closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{vol}(R):=\prod_{i=1}^{n}(b_{i}-a_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
partition 
\series default
of the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 is a set of real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{0},\dots,p_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=p_{0}<p_{1}<\cdots<p_{n}=b.
\]

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
partition 
\series default
of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{P_{1},\dots,P_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, where each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $[a_{i},b_{i}]$
\end_inset

.
 The partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 divides the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 into closed subrectangles, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define the 
\series bold
lower sum 
\series default
and the 
\series bold
upper sum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P):=\sum_{R_{j}}\left(\inf_{R_{j}}f\right)\text{vol}(R_{j}),\qquad U(f,P):=\sum_{R_{j}}\left(\sup_{R_{j}}f\right)\text{vol}(R_{j}),
\]

\end_inset

where each sum runs over all subrectangles of the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 For any partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $L(f,P)\leq U(f,P)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, more is true: for any two partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq U(f,P'),
\]

\end_inset

which we show next.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P'=\{P_{1}',\dots,P_{n}'\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
refinement 
\series default
of the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{P_{1},\dots,P_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\subset P_{i}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is a refinement of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, then each subrectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is subdivided into subrectangles 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{jk}'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

, and it is easily seen that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq L(f,P'),
\]

\end_inset

because if 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{jk}'\subset R_{j}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf_{R_{j}}f\leq\inf_{R_{jk}'}f$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is a refinement of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(f,P')\leq U(f,P).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Any two partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 have a common refinement 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\{Q_{1},\dots,Q_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}=P_{i}\cup P_{i}'$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq L(f,Q)\leq U(f,Q)\leq U(f,P').
\]

\end_inset

It follows that the supremum of the lower sum 
\begin_inset Formula $L(f,P)$
\end_inset

 over all partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is less than or equal to the infimum of the upper sum 
\begin_inset Formula $U(f,P)$
\end_inset

 over all partitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We define these two numbers to be the 
\series bold
lower integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

 
\series default
and the 
\series bold
upper integral 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

, respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\int}_{R}f:=\sup_{P}L(f,P),\qquad\overline{\int}_{R}f:=\inf_{P}L(f,P).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a closed rectangle in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:R\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
Riemann integrable 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\int}_{R}f=\overline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

; in this case, the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is this common value, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{R}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a bounded monotone increasing function on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 Indeed, consider the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}=\{p_{0}<p_{1}<\cdots<p_{2n-1}<p_{2n}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=-1+i/3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U(f,P_{n})-L(f,P_{n}) & =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{2n}f(-1+i/3)-\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=0}^{2n-1}f(-1+i/3)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{2n}f(-1+i/3)-\sum_{i=0}^{2n-1}f(-1+i/3)\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\left(f(1)-f(-1)\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then the 
\series bold
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by zero 
\series default
is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(x)=\begin{cases}
f(x) & \text{if }x\in A,\\
0 & \text{if }x\notin A.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded function on a bounded set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Enclose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in a closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and define the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}=\int_{R}\widetilde{f}(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}
\]

\end_inset

if the right-hand side exists.
 In this way we can deal with the integral of a bounded function whose domain
 is an arbitrary bounded set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
volume 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\text{vol}(A)$
\end_inset

 of a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{A}1dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 if the integral exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integrability Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we describe some conditions under which a function defined
 on an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is said to have 
\series bold
measure zero 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there is a countable cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{R_{i}\}_{i=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by closed rectangles 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\text{vol}(R_{i})<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}(Lebesgue's theorem)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 on a bounded subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable if and only if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Disc}(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

 of discontinuities of the extended function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 has measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcontextriemint}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has compact support, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Being continuous on a compact set, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Being compact, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, the extended function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as well.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, there is an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 On this open ball, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}=0$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By Lebesgue's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-1,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tan(\pi x/2)$
\end_inset

, is defined on an open subset of finite length in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but it not bounded.
 The support of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

, which is not compact.
 Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy the hypotheses of either Lebesgue's theorem or 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propcontextriemint})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Note that it is not Riemann integrable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
domain of integration 
\series default
if it is bounded and its topological boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{bd}(A)$
\end_inset

 is a set of measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every bounded continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on a domain of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by zero.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is necessarily continuous at all interior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous at all exterior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 also, because every exterior point has a neighborhood contained entirely
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash A$
\end_inset

, on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is identically zero.
 Therefore, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Disc}(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

 of discontinuities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial(A)$
\end_inset

, a set of measure zero.
 By Lebesgue's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Integral of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-Form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once a set of coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 has been fixed on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be identified with functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, since every 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 for a unique function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way the theory of Riemann integration of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 carries over to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, with standard coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Its 
\series bold
integral 
\series default
over a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset U$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}\omega=\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}:=\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n},
\]

\end_inset

if the Riemann integral exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a bounded continuous function defined on a domain of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us see how the integral of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=fdx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 transforms under a change of variables.
 A change of variables on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is given by a diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset V\to U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},\dots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}:=x_{i}\circ T$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are connected, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dT_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dT_{n}=\text{det}\left(J(T)\right)dy_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dy_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{V}T^{*}\omega & =\int_{V}(T^{*}f)T^{*}dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge T^{*}dx_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)dT_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dT_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)\det(J(T))dy_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dy_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)\det(J(T))dy_{1}\cdots dy_{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

On the other hand, the change-of-variables formula from advanced calculus
 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega=\int_{U}fdx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}=\int_{V}(f\circ T)|\det(J(T))|dy_{1}\cdots dy_{n},
\]

\end_inset

with an absolute-value sign around the Jacobian determinant.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}T^{*}\omega=\pm\int_{U}\omega,
\]

\end_inset

depending on whether the Jacobian determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(J(T))$
\end_inset

 is positive or negative.
 In particular, the integral of a differential form is not invariant under
 all diffeomorphisms of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, but only under orientation-preserving diffeomorphisms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integral of a Differential Form over a Manifold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integration of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is not so different from integration of a function.
 Our approach to integration over a general manifold has several distinguishing
 features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold must be oriented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one can integrate only 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, not functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms must have compact support.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an oriented manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, with an oriented atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 giving the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{c}^{k}(M)$
\end_inset

 the vector space of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-forms with compact support on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart in this atlas.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(U)$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega=\int_{\phi(U)}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega.
\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is another chart in the oriented atlas with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\psi^{-1}\psi(U)\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is an orientation-preserving diffeomorphism, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\phi(U)}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega=\int_{\psi(U)}(\phi\circ\psi^{-1})^{*}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega=\int_{\psi(U)}(\psi^{-1})^{*}\omega.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U}\omega$
\end_inset

 on a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of the atlas is well defined, independent of the choice of coordinates
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 By linearity of the integral on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\tau\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(U)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega+\tau=\int_{U}\omega+\int_{U}\tau.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 subordinate to the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has compact support and a partition of unity has locally finite supports,
 all except finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 are identically zero.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\sum_{\alpha}\rho_{\alpha}\omega
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\emph on
finite 
\emph default
sum.
 Also since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\left(\rho_{\alpha}\omega\right)\subset\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha})\cap\text{supp}(\omega)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha}\omega)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of the compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha}\omega)$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support in the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, its integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 Therefore, we can define the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be the finite sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{M}\omega:=\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega.\label{eq:integralofnform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For this integral to be well defined, we must show that it is independent
 of the choices of oriented atlas and partition of unity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

 be another oriented atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 specifying the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\chi_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

 a partition of unity subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta},\phi_{\alpha}|_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}})\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta}|_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}})\}$
\end_inset

 are two new atlases of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 specifying the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega & =\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\chi_{\beta}\omega & (\text{because }\sum_{\beta}\chi_{\beta}=1)\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}\omega & (\text{these are finite sums})\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\int_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}}\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}\omega,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last line follows from the fact that the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 By symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\beta}\int_{V_{\beta}}\chi_{\beta}\omega$
\end_inset

 is equal to the same sum.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega=\sum_{\beta}\int_{V_{\beta}}\chi_{\beta}\omega,
\]

\end_inset

proving that the integral 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integralofnform})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quotients and Gluing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many important topological spaces (and manifolds) that are constructed
 by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

identifying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pieces of spaces.
 This typically takes the form of gluing along open sets or passing to quotients
 by (reasonable) equivalence relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Quotient Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that an equivalence relation on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a reflexive, symmetric, and transitive relation.
 The 
\series bold
equivalence class 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is the set of all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into disjoint equivalence classes.
 We denote the set of equivalence classes by 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 and call this set the 
\series bold
quotient 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural 
\series bold
projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/\sim$
\end_inset

 
\series default
that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 to its equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assume now that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space.
 We define a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 by declaring a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 to be open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, both the empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and the entire quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 are open.
 Further, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}\right)=\bigcup_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}\left(U_{i}\right)\text{ and }\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}U_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}\left(U_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

the collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed under arbitrary unions and finite intersections, and is therefore
 a topology.
 It is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 With this topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
quotient space 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 The way we defined the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 makes the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Continuity of a Map on a Quotient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and is constant on each equivalence class.
 Then it induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:X/\sim\to Y$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}([x])=f(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:X/\sim\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous if and only if the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\overline{f}\circ\pi$
\end_inset

 is a composition of two continuous functions.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)=\pi^{-1}\left(\overline{f}^{-1}(V)\right)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of quotient topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 was arbitary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Identification of a Subset to a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim x\text{ for all }x\in X\text{ and }x\sim y\text{ for all }x,y\in A.
\]

\end_inset

This is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\series bold
identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to a point
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the quotient space obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 by identifying the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 to a point.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 the unit circle in the complex plane.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:I\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=e^{2\pi ix}$
\end_inset

, assumes the same value at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and so induces a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:I/\sim\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 As the continuous image of a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous bijection from the compact space 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 to the Hausdorff space 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence it is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Open Equivalence Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

An equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In other words, the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if for every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(U))=\bigcup_{x\in U}[x]
\]

\end_inset

of all points equivalent to some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be the equivalence relation on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that identifies the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the projection map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is not an open map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-2,0)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(V))=(-2,0)\cup\{1\},
\]

\end_inset

which is not open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 that defines the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)\in X\times X\mid x\sim y\}.
\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
graph 
\series default
of the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremquotientishausdorff}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff if and only if the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is a sequence of equivalent statements: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U\times V)\cap R=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 iff for every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $x\not\sim y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 iff for any two points 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)\cap\pi(V)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now show that this last statement is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 being Hausdorff.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]$
\end_inset

 respectively, so 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exist disjoint open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]\in B$
\end_inset

.
 By the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(\pi^{-1}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(\pi^{-1}B)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\pi^{-1}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\pi^{-1}B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{B_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B(\alpha)\}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in W$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

 is open, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B\subset\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]=\pi(x)\in\pi(B)\subset W$
\end_inset

, which proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $S/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a second-countable space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then the quotient space is second-countable.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotients by Group Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Many important manifolds are constructed as quotients by actions of groups
 on other manifolds, and this often provides a useful way to understand
 spaces that may have been constructed by other means.
 As a basic example, the Klein bottle will be defined as a quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 by the action of a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The circle as defined concretely in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by additive translation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 a discrete group.
 A right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
continuous 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 the action map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x.g$
\end_inset

 is continuous (and hence a homeomorphism, as the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 gives an inverse).
 The action is 
\series bold
free 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stabilizer subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\in G\mid x.g=x\}$
\end_inset

 is the trivial subgroup (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g=x$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

).
 The action is 
\series bold
properly discontinuous
\series default
 when it is continuous for the discrete topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-translate 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\times G\to X$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose we have a right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{g}:=g^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(U)=\bigcup_{g\in G}U_{g}\times\{g\},
\]

\end_inset

which is open.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{g}:=g^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(U)\cap X\times\{g\}=U_{g}\times\{g\},
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times\{g\}$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a locally Hausdorff space, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on the right via a properly discontinuous action.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we get an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 This property is unaffected by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 with a smaller open subset around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so by the locally Hausdorff property we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 The key is that we can do better: there exists an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x.g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if the action is also free then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To find 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in G$
\end_inset

 be an enumeration of the finite set of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

.
 For any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 we can only have 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U.g\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 equal to one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

's, so it suffices to show that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\in U_{x}\backslash\{x\}$
\end_inset

 there is an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap(U_{i}).g_{i}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (and then we may take 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 to be the intersection of the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

's over the finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\neq x$
\end_inset

).
 By the Hausdorff property of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}\in U_{x}\backslash\{x\}$
\end_inset

 there exist disjoint opens 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i},V_{i}'\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x.g_{i}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 By continuity of the action on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}\in G$
\end_inset

 there is an open 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(W_{i}).g_{i}\subseteq V'_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=W_{i}\cap V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $V'_{i}$
\end_inset

 yet satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i}).g_{i}\subseteq V'_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap(U_{i}).g_{i}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The interest in free and properly discontinuous actions is that for such
 actions in the locally Hausdorff case we may find an open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 around each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for such actions we may say that in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 we are identifying points in the same 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbit with this identification process not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crushing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by identifying points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are arbitrarly close to each other.
 An example where things go horribly wrong is the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via additive translations.
 This is a continuous action, but the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}/\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is very bad: any two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

-orbits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 contain arbitrarily close points! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here are some examples of free and properly discontinuous actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The antipodal map on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n+1})\mapsto(-a_{1},\dots,-a_{n+1})$
\end_inset

, viewed as an action of the integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is free and properly discontinuous: freeness is clear, as is continuity,
 and for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 the points near 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 all have their antipodes far away! 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $X:=\mathbf{V}(x^{3}+y^{3}+z^{3}-1)\subseteq\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the action 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})\mapsto(\zeta_{3}a_{1},\zeta_{3}a_{2},\zeta_{3})$
\end_inset

, viewed as an action of the integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 is free and properly discontinuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be a product of two circles, where the circle 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{z\in\mathbb{C}\mid|z|=1\}
\]

\end_inset

is viewed as a topological group (using multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, so both the group law and inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto1/z=\overline{z}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are continuous).
 The visibly continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $(z,w)\mapsto(1/z,-w)=(\overline{z},-w)$
\end_inset

 reflects through the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis in the first circle and rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $180$
\end_inset

-degree in the second circle, and it is its own inverse.
 Thus, this give an action by the order-
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of integers mod 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The associated quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 will be called the (set-theoretic) 
\series bold
Klein bottle
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally Hausdorff topological space with a free and properly discontinuous
 action by a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 There is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

 such that the quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map that is a local homeomorphism (i.e.
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits a neighborhood mapping homeomorphically onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X/G$
\end_inset

).
 Moreover, the quotient map is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq X/G$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if its preimage in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an open set that is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U.g$
\end_inset

 for all nontrivial 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its open image 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 and the natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times G\to\pi^{-1}(\overline{U})$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,g)\mapsto u.g$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism when 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is given the discrete topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The topology in this theorem is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
, and it is locally Hausdorff since 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sketch: we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 The inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a disjoint union of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{g\in G}U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be any open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(U)=\pi\left(\bigcup_{x\in U}U_{x}\right)=\bigcup_{x\in U}\pi(U_{x})
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Mbius Strip) Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(-a,a)\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and let the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 act on it with the non-trivial element acting by 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\mapsto(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 This is easily checked to be a continuous action for the discrete topology
 of the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and it is free and properly discontinuous.
 The quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Mbius strip 
\series default
of height 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To check that the Mbius strip 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, we use the quotient criterion: the set of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 with the form 
\begin_inset Formula $((t,w),(t',w'))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(t,w)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

 is checked to be closed by using the sequential criterion in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\sim(t'_{n},w'_{n})$
\end_inset

 are sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 which converge 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\sim(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\neq(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and such that eventually 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\neq(t_{n}',w_{n}')$
\end_inset

 (We can do this because they converge to different limits and our space
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff).
 Thus, eventually we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n}',w_{n}')=(-t_{n},-w_{n})\to(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mbius Strip in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that the Mbius strip 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 (with height 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

) was defined as an abstract smooth manifold made as a quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $(-a,a)\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 by a free and properly discontinuous action by the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Using the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}/2\pi\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mapsto(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)$
\end_inset

, we consider the standard parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as a local coordinate on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For finite 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(t,\theta)\mapsto(2a\cos2\theta+t\cos\theta\cos2\theta,2a\sin2\theta+t\cos\theta\sin2\theta,t\sin\theta).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(-t,\pi+\theta)=f(t,\theta)$
\end_inset

 by inspection, it follows from the universal property of the quotient map
 
\begin_inset Formula $(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to M_{a}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 uniquely factors through this via a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:M_{a}\to\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Our goal is to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is an embedding and to use this viewpoint to understand some basic properties
 of the Mbius strip.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is an immersion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first reduce the problem to working with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is given by a simple explicit formula across its entire domain (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 does not have global coordinates.
 Of course, working locally for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the same
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as working locally for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, so the reduction step to working with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 isn't really necessary if one says things a little differently.
 However, it seems a bit cleaner to just make the reduction step right away
 and so to thereby work with the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that feel a bit more concrete than the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 at the global level.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to M_{a}$
\end_inset

 be the natural quotient map.
 Each point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the Chain Rule gives that the injection 
\begin_inset Formula $df(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $d\overline{f}(p(\xi_{0}))\circ dp(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $dp(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 an isomorphism (as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a local 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism, via the theory of quotients by free and properly discontinuous
 group actions).
 Hence, the tangent map for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is injective at 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 if and only if the tangent map for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is injective at 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore enough (even equivalent!) to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an immersion.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Construction of Manifolds From Gluing Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The definition of a manifold assumes that the underlying set, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, is already known.
 However, there are situations where we only have some indirect information
 about the overlap of the domains 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the local charts defining our manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, in terms of the transition functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}:\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})\to\phi_{j}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}),
\]

\end_inset

but where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 itself is not known.
 Our goal in this subsection is to try and reconstruct a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by gluing open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 using the transition functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defngluingmanifold}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be an integer with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be either an integer with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 A set of 
\series bold
gluing data 
\series default
is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}=((\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K}),
\]

\end_inset

satisfying the following properties, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a (nonempty) countable set and 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\{(i,j)\in I\times I\mid\Omega_{ij}\neq\emptyset\}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 called a 
\series bold
parametrization domain
\series default
, for short, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-domain
\series default
, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise disjoint (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}\cap\Omega_{j})=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in I\times I$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ii}=\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Each nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

) is called a 
\series bold
gluing domain
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}:\Omega_{ij}\to\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 bijection for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 called a 
\series bold
transition function 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
gluing function
\series default
) and the following condition holds:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
cocycle condition 
\series default
holds: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\cap\Omega_{jk}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk})\subseteq\Omega_{ik}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ki}(x)=(\phi_{kj}\circ\phi_{ji})(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{ji}\cap\Omega_{jk})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\partial(\Omega_{ij})\cap\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\partial(\Omega_{ji})\cap\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

, there are open balls, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, so that no point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}\cap\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the image of any point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\cap\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In practical applications, the index set, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, is of course finite and the open subsets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, may have special properties (for example, connected; open simplicies,
 etc.).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}\subseteq\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\subseteq\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint, so are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The cocycle condition may seem overly complicated but it is actually needed
 to guarantee the transitivity of the relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, which we will define shortly.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

 are bijections, the cocycle condition implies the following conditions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ii}=\text{id}_{\Omega_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This follows by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j=k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}=\phi_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from (a) and by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $k=i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on it.
 Then set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}=\phi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}=\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}:\Omega_{ji}\to\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding transition maps.
 Then it's easy to check that the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

, and the gluing functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}$
\end_inset

, satisfy the conditions of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defngluingmanifold})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk}) & =(\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1})(\phi_{j}(U_{j}\cap U_{k}))\\
 & =\phi_{i}(U_{j}\cap U_{k})\\
 & =\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k})\\
 & \subseteq\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{k})\\
 & =\Omega_{ik}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us show that a set of gluing data defines a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold in a natural way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For every set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, whose transition functions are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define the binary relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, on the disjoint union, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega:=\coprod_{i\in I}\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the open sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, as follows: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim y\text{ if and only if there exists }(i,j)\in K\text{ such that }x\in\Omega_{ij},\text{ }y\in\Omega_{ji},\text{ and }y=\phi_{ji}(x).
\]

\end_inset

The cocycle condition ensures that this is an equivalence relation.
 Indeed, (a) implies reflexivity and (b) implies symmetry.
 The crucial step is to check transitivity.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim z$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are some 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}(x)=y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{kj}(y)=z$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{kj}\circ\phi_{ji})(x)=\phi_{ki}(x)=z$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

, as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\mathcal{G}}:=\Omega/\sim
\]

\end_inset

be the quotient space by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=\coprod_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\pi\left(U\right)\right)=\coprod_{i\in I}\left(\bigcup_{j\in I}\phi_{ij}\left(U_{j}\cap\Omega_{ji}\right)\cup U_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\left(U_{j}\cap\Omega_{ji}\right)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is second-countable since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is second-countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation, we can use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremquotientishausdorff})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff by showing that the graph 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\left\{ (x,y)\in\Omega\times\Omega\mid x\sim y\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\times\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by showing that if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\Omega\times\Omega$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in R$
\end_inset

.
 That is to say, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\Omega_{i}\times\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})\in\Omega_{i}\times\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 (since it will eventually be in there anyways).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=y_{n}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In order for us to have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

, then it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

 in arbitrarily small neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we need to show that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\partial(\Omega_{ij})\cap\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\partial(\Omega_{ji})\cap\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open balls 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 so that no point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}\cap\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the image of any point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\cap\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies that no point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to some point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\to y$
\end_inset

, as the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})$
\end_inset

 must eventually be in the neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{in}_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to\coprod_{i\in I}\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the natural injection and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}:=\pi\circ\text{in}_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to M_{\mathcal{G}}.
\]

\end_inset

Since we already noted that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, we conclude that every 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=\tau_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, it is immediately verified that the 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 are charts and this collection of charts forms a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk})\subseteq\Omega_{ik}$
\end_inset

 is needed in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 to be transitive.
 The picture below illustrates how things could go wrong:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cocyclecondition.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobius Strip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to give this set the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all nonvertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonvertical is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid y=ax+b\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}:U_{v}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}\mapsto(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all nonhorizontal lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonhorizontal is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x=cy+d\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}:U_{h}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}\mapsto(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}\cup U_{h}=X$
\end_inset

.
 To get a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we glue the topologies from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{h}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{vh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{hv}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{vh}(c,d) & =\varphi_{v}\circ\varphi_{h}^{-1}(c,d)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{c,d}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{hv}(a,b) & =\varphi_{h}\circ\varphi_{v}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{a,b}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether, our gluing data consists of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega_{1}=\Omega_{2}=\mathbb{R}^{2},\qquad\Omega_{12}=\Omega_{21}=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\},\qquad\phi_{12}:(a,b)\mapsto\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This manifold is called the 
\series bold
Mobius strip
\series default
.
 We can visualize it as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Mobiusstrip.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can describe this manifold in another way as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be the group given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G:=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{R}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

The group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a natural open subgroup
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Aff}(\mathbb{R})=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{R}\text{ and }a\neq0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 can be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}=\Omega_{2}=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Aff}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 can be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{12}=\Omega_{21}=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these identifications, the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}$
\end_inset

 is identified with the inverse map! Indeed, the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1/a & -b/a\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given a set of gluing data, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, it is natural to consider the collection of manifolds, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, parametrized by maps, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to M$
\end_inset

, whose domains are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

's and whose transition functions are given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

's, that is, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

We will say that such manifolds are 
\series bold
induced 
\series default
by the set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The parametrization maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the property: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})\cap\tau_{j}(\Omega_{j})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 and if so, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})\cap\tau_{j}(\Omega_{j})=\tau_{i}(\Omega_{ij})=\tau_{j}(\Omega_{ji}).
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, they also satisfy the consistency condition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}=\tau_{j}\circ\phi_{ji},
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a manifold induced by the set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

's are injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, the two properties stated above for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

's also hold for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 We will see that the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

universal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 manifold induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 in the sense that every manifold induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 by some 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Interestingly, it is possible to characterize when two manifolds induced
 by the same set of gluing data are isomorphic in terms of a condition on
 their transition functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given any set of gluing data, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, for any two manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 given by families of parametrizations 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega_{i},\theta_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega_{i},\theta'_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, respectively, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to M'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism, then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 bijections, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}:W_{ij}\to W'_{ij},$
\end_inset

 for some open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij},W'_{ij}\subseteq\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}'(x)=\rho_{j}\circ\phi_{ji}\circ\rho_{i}^{-1}(x),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}'=\theta'{}_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta'{}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}=(\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i})\mid_{W_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 to itself and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i}(\Omega_{ij})=\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij}=W'_{ij}=\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{locallyringedspacesdefn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Structures to Maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Atlases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty open set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:(U,\mathcal{O}\mid_{U})\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-isomorphism onto an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 given its usual 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structure).
 The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas because of two facts: a composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 maps is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

, and for maps between opens in finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 is the same as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notion (in terms of structured 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-spaces).
 It is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is standardized.
 We want to prove that the standardized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is maximal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From Maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Atlases to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal standarized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For any non-empty open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 to be the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, the composite map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 that is the target of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\emptyset)=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\mapsto\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on the open domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in a Euclidean space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The usual notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on an open set in a Euclidean space is preserved under restirction
 to smaller opens and can be checked by working on an open covering.
 Thus, the first claim in the lemma follows easily from the definition of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Homological Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chain Complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A 
\series bold
chain complex
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A:=(A_{\bullet},d_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, or simply a 
\series bold
chain complex 
\series default
if the context is clear, is a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 and morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}:A_{i}\to A_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramA}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} (A,d) := 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d _{i+1}"] & A_i  
\backslash
arrow[r," d _i "] & A_{i-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\circ d_{i+1}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\circ d_{i+1}=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d_{i})\supset\text{Im}(d_{i+1})$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, we define the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th
\series default
 
\series bold
homology of the chain complex
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{i}(A):=\text{Ker}(d_{i})/\text{Im}(d_{i+1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
chain map
\series default
 between two complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A_{\bullet},d_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'=(A'_{\bullet},d'_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\bullet}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:A_{i}\to A'_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\varphi_{i-1}=\varphi_{i}d_{i-1}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the definition that a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 induces map of homologies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:H_{i}(A)\to H_{i}(A')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To simplify notation in what follows, we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 as a trivially graded ring.
 If 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramA}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} A := 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d _{i+1}"] & A_i  
\backslash
arrow[r," d _i "] & A_{i-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a chain complex over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module together with an graded endomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $d:A\to A$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 as being the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
homology 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $H(A):=\text{Ker}(d)/\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(A)=\bigoplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}H_{i}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 An element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
cycle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
boundary 
\series default
of
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 be chain complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 A chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a homogeneous homomorphism of graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi d=d'\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the definition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 gies rise to an 
\series bold
induced map on homology
\series default
, which we also call 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:H(A)\to H(A')$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}(A)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:H_{i}(A)\to H_{i}(A')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Homotopy Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 be chain maps of chain complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
homotopic 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 if there is a graded homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi=d'h+hd$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 be chain maps of chain complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is homotopic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 induce the same map on homology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi$
\end_inset

 induces the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 map on homology.
 Thus we may simplify the notation by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi$
\end_inset

, and assume from the outset that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 be a homotopy, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=d'h+dh$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 be a cycle of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 From the formula for the homotopy 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a) & =d'(h(a))+h(d(a))\\
 & =d'(h(a))+h(0)\\
 & =d'(h(a)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)$
\end_inset

 is a boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 map on homology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exact Sequences of Chain Complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A''$
\end_inset

 be chain complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d''$
\end_inset

 respectively, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A'\to A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:A\to A''$
\end_inset

 be chain maps.
 Then we say that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A' 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "]  & A 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi "]  & A'' 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a 
\series bold
short exact sequence 
\series default
of chain complexes if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A'_i 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _i"]  & A_i 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _i"]  & A'' _i 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the rows in the diagram below are exact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=30] & 
\backslash
vdots 
\backslash
arrow[d, "d' _{i+2}"]  & 
\backslash
vdots 
\backslash
arrow[d, "d _{i+2}" ]   & 
\backslash
vdots 
\backslash
arrow[d , "d'' _{i+2}"] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A'_{i+1}   
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _{i+1}"] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "d' _{i+1} " ] & A_{i+1}   
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _{i+1}"] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "d _{i+1} " ] & A''_{i+1}   
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "d'' _{i+1} " ] & 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


