\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
deRham Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y)=\langle P(x,y),Q(x,y)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a smooth vector field representing a force on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a parametrized curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)=(x(t),y(t))$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq t\leq b$
\end_inset

.
 Then the work done by the force in moving a particle from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is given by the line integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{C}Pdx+Qdy$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Such a line integral is easy to compute if the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the gradient of a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\text{grad}f=\langle\partial_{x}f,\partial_{y}f\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

By Stoke's theorem, the line integral is simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{C}\partial_{x}fdx+\partial_{y}fdy=\int_{C}df=f(q)-f(p).
\]

\end_inset

A necessary condition for the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\langle P,Q\rangle$
\end_inset

 to be a gradient is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{y}=\partial_{y}\partial_{x}f=\partial_{x}\partial_{y}f=Q_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question is now the following: if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{y}-Q_{x}=0$
\end_inset

, is the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\langle P,Q\rangle$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 the gradient of some scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

? In terms of differential forms, the question becomes the following: if
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=Pdx+Qdy$
\end_inset

 is closed on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, is it exact? The answer to this question is sometimes yes and sometimes
 no, depending on the topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
de Rham Complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 denote the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{0}(M):=C^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have the following cochain complex over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramomega}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} ( 
\backslash
Omega (M),d) := & 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
Omega ^0 (M) 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d"] & 
\backslash
Omega ^1 (M)  
\backslash
arrow[r," d  "] & 
\backslash
Omega ^2 (M) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "d" ] & 
\backslash
cdots, 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 denotes the exterior derivative.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the cohomology of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

 and call it the 
\series bold
deRham cohomology 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the cycles of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the boundaries of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components, then its de Rham cohomology in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(M)=\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 An element of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(M)$
\end_inset

 is specified by an ordered- 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-tuple of real numbers, each real number representing a constant function
 on a connected component of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since there are no nonzero exact 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-forms, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{0}(M)=Z^{0}(M).
\]

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a closed 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $df=0$
\end_inset

.
 On any chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
df=\sum_{\lambda=1}^{n}(\partial_{x_{\lambda}}f)dx_{\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $df=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if and only if all the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{\lambda}}f$
\end_inset

 vanish identically on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 being locally constant on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the closed 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are precisely the locally constant functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function must be constant on each connected component on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components, then a locally constant function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be specified by an ordered set of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 real numbers.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{0}(M)=\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the de Rham cohomology 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{k}(M)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 is a vector space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}\in A_{k}(T_{p}M)$
\end_inset

, the space of alternating 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-linear functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}(T_{p}M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

, the only 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the zero form.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of de Rham Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (De Rham cohomology of the real line) Since the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is connected, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{0}(\mathbb{R}^{1})=\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

For dimensional reasons, there are no nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that every 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)dx$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is exact if and only if three is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)dx=dg=g'(x)dx,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)$
\end_inset

 is the calculus derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is simply an antiderivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, for example 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt.
\]

\end_inset

This proves that every 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(\mathbb{R}^{1})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (De Rham cohomology of the circle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the unit circle in the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

-plane.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is connected, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(S^{1})=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{k}(S^{1})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(S^{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=(\cos t,\sin t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $i:[0,2\pi]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the inclusion map.
 Restricting the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2\pi]$
\end_inset

 gives a parametrization 
\begin_inset Formula $F:=h\circ i:[0,2\pi]\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 of the circle.
 A nowhere-vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=-ydx+xdy$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h^{*}\omega & =-\sin td(\cos t)+\cos td(\sin t)\\
 & =(\sin^{2}t+\cos^{2}t)dt\\
 & =dt.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F^{*}\omega & =i^{*}h^{*}\omega\\
 & =i^{*}dt\\
 & =dt,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{S^{1}}\omega & =\int_{F([0,2\pi])}\omega\\
 & =\int_{[0,2\pi]}F^{*}\omega\\
 & =\int_{0}^{2\pi}dt\\
 & =2\pi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the cirle has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, all 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are closed, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{1}(S^{1})=Z^{1}(S^{1})$
\end_inset

.
 The integration of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 defines a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:Z^{1}(S^{1})=\Omega^{1}(S^{1})\to\mathbb{R},\quad\varphi(\alpha)=\int_{S^{1}}\alpha.
\]

\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\omega)=2\pi\neq0$
\end_inset

, the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\Omega^{1}(S^{1})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is onto.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By Stokes's theorem, the exact 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, we will show that all 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 are exact.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=f\omega$
\end_inset

 is a smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}=h^{*}f=f\circ h\in\Omega^{0}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is periodic of period 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\int_{S^{1}}\alpha\\
 & =\int_{F([0,2\pi])}F^{*}\alpha\\
 & =\int_{[0,2\pi]}(i^{*}h^{*}f)(t)\cdot F^{*}\omega\\
 & =\int_{0}^{2\pi}\overline{f}(t)dt.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Hairy Ball Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd then there exists a nowhere-vanishing smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2k+1$
\end_inset

 the consider the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}=\mathbb{R}^{2k+2}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=(-x_{2}\partial_{x_{1}}+x_{1}\partial_{x_{2}})+\cdots+(-x_{2k+2}\partial_{x_{2k+1}}+x_{2k+1}\partial_{x_{2k+2}})=\sum_{j=0}^{k}(-x_{2j+2}\partial_{x_{2j+1}}+x_{2j+1}\partial_{x_{2j+2}}).
\]

\end_inset

For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{2k+2})$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the line spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

, so it lies in the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to this line.
 In other words, the smooth section 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 of the pullback bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(T(\mathbb{R}^{n+1}))|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 takes values in the subbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T(S^{n})$
\end_inset

, which is to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth vector field on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a visibly nowhere-vanishing vector field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The above construction does not work if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, so there arises the question of whether there exists a nowhere-vanishi
ng smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 for even 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The answer is negative, and is called the 
\series bold
hairy ball 
\series default
theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 must vanish somewhere if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, and assume that it is nowhere-vanishing.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}:[0,\pi/\|\vec{v}(p)\|]\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the smooth parametric great circle (with constant speed) going from
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-p$
\end_inset

 with velocity vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}'(0)=\vec{v}(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 (This would not make sense if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Working in the plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, we get the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{p}(t)=\cos\left(t\|\vec{v}(p)\|\right)p+\sin\left(t\|\vec{v}(p)\right)\frac{\vec{v}(p)}{\|\vec{v}(p)\|}\in S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(These algebraic formulas would not make sense if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 vanishes somewhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

).
 Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mapping 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F:S^{n}\times[0,1]\to S^{n},
\]

\end_inset

defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,t)\mapsto\gamma_{p}(\pi t/\|\vec{v}(p)\|)$
\end_inset

.
 The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 makes it clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map (and is continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is merely continuous and nowhere-vanishing).
 Now obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p,0)=p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p,1)=-p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 defines a smooth homotopy from the identity map on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 to the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mapsto-p$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 (and is a continuous homotopy if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is merely continuous and nowhere-vanishing).
 Thus, to prove the hairy ball theorem we just have to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even then the identity and antipodal maps 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 are not smoothly homotopic to each other; likewise to get the continuous
 version we just need to prove that there is no continuous homotopy deforming
 one of these maps into the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove the 
\emph on
non-existence 
\emph default
of such a homotopy, we shall use the (smooth) homotopy invariance of deRham
 cohomology.
 Indeed, by this homotopy-invariance we get that under the existence of
 such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $A:S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 induces the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}:\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{k}(S^{n})\to\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{k}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th deRham cohomology of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us focus on the case 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

.
 To get a contradiction, we just have to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 as a self-map of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
the identity map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\sum_{i=1}^{n+1}(-1)^{i-1}x_{i}dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge\widehat{dx}_{i}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega=(n+1)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, so for the unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 with its standard orientation we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{B^{n+1}}d\omega=(n+1)\text{vol}(B^{n+1})\neq0.
\]

\end_inset

By Stokes' theorem for 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\omega|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 and we give 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}=\partial B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 the induced boundary orientation, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S^{n}}\eta=\int_{B^{n+1}}d\omega\neq0.
\]

\end_inset

Hence, by Stokes' theorem for the boundaryless smooth compact oriented manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 we conclude that the top-degree differential form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is not exact.
 That is, its deRham cohomology class 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]\in H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is non-zero.
 (Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is not closed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, but its pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is necessarily closed on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 purely for elementary reasons, as 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By the existence of the smooth homotopy between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the identity map, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is the identity map, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[A^{*}(\eta)]=A^{*}([\eta])$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the top-degree differential forms 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}(\eta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 differ by an exact form.
 But the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $A:S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the negation map 
\begin_inset Formula $N:\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\to\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, and by inspection of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{\mathbb{R}^{n+1}}^{n}(\mathbb{R}^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{*}(\omega)=(-1)^{n+1}\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, pulling back this equality to the sphere gives 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}(\eta)=(-1)^{n+1}\eta$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{S^{n}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\eta]=A^{*}([\eta])=[A^{*}(\eta)]=[(-1)^{n+1}\eta]=(-1)^{n+1}[\eta].
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even we therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]=-[\eta]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]=0.$
\end_inset

 But we have already seen via Stokes' theorem for the boundaryless manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and for the manifold with boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 This completes the proof.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R}):=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid ad-bc=1\right\} \subset\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be a path in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=\begin{pmatrix}a(t) & b(t)\\
c(t) & d(t)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=I:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then by differentiating the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)d(t)-b(t)c(t)=1$
\end_inset

 and evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\dot{a}(0)d(0)+a(0)\dot{d}(0)-\dot{b}(0)c(0)-b(0)\dot{c}(0)\\
 & =\dot{a}(0)+\dot{d}(0).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Or 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{a}(0)=-\dot{d}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tr}\left(\dot{\gamma}(0)\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose we have a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tr}(A)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Can we find a path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(0)=A$
\end_inset

? Indeed, we can.
 The matrix exponential works: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{tA}:=I+A+\frac{1}{2}A^{2}+\frac{1}{6}A^{3}+\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

This is because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{tA}\right) & =\frac{d}{dt}\left(I+tA+\frac{1}{2}t^{2}A^{2}+\frac{1}{6}t^{3}A^{3}+\cdots\right)\\
 & =\frac{d}{dt}(I)+\frac{d}{dt}(tA)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d}{dt}(t^{2}A^{2})+\frac{1}{6}\frac{d}{dt}(t^{3}A^{3})+\cdots\\
 & =A+tA^{2}+\frac{1}{2}t^{2}A^{3}+\cdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{tA}\right)_{\mid t=0}=A$
\end_inset

.
 Also we have 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{tA}\in\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{det}(e^{tA}) & =e^{\text{Tr}(tA)}\\
 & =e^{0}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R}):=\left\{ A\in\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid AA^{t}=I\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be a path in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=\begin{pmatrix}a(t) & b(t)\\
c(t) & d(t)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=I:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then by differentiating the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\gamma(t)\gamma(t)^{t}$
\end_inset

 and evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\dot{\gamma}(0)\gamma(0)^{t}+\gamma(0)\dot{\gamma}(0)^{t}\\
 & =\dot{\gamma}(0)+\dot{\gamma}(0)^{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(0)$
\end_inset

 is a skew-symmetric matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Field in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 be a vector field in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega:=(0,y,0):=y\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's find a path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}=\omega(\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
 A general path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=(a(t),b(t),c(t))\qquad\text{and}\qquad\dot{\gamma}(t)=(\dot{a}(t),\dot{b}(t),\dot{c}(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega($
\end_inset

So we need 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{a}(t) & =0\\
\dot{b}(t) & =b(t)\\
\dot{c}(t) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=(a(0),b(0)e^{t},c(0))$
\end_inset

 works.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lie Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
Lie group 
\series default
is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 that is also a group such that the two group operations, multiplication
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\times G\to G,\qquad(a,b)\mapsto ab,
\]

\end_inset

and inverse
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\to G,\qquad a\mapsto a^{-1},
\]

\end_inset

are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

, denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}:G\to G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}(x)=ax$
\end_inset

, the operation of 
\series bold
left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
, and by 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}:G\to G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}(x)=xa$
\end_inset

, the operation of 
\series bold
right multiplication 
\series default
by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 We also call left and right multiplications 
\series bold
left 
\series default
and 
\series bold
right translations
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Actually smoothness of invsersion can be dropped from the definition of
 a Lie Group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold and suppose it is equipped with a group structure such that the
 composition law 
\begin_inset Formula $m:G\times G\to G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $G\to G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shearing transformation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma:G\times G\to G\times G,
\]

\end_inset

defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(g,h)=(g,gh)$
\end_inset

.
 This is bijective since we are using a group law, and it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 since the composition law 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 (Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $M,M',M''$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds, a map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M'\times M''$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its component maps 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M''$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, due to the nature of product manifold structures.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 Granting this, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} G=
\backslash
{ e 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
times G  
\backslash
arrow[r] & G 
\backslash
times G 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
Sigma ^-1 "]  & G 
\backslash
times G 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, but explicitely this composite map is 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto(g,g^{-1})$
\end_inset

, so its second component 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bijection, the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 property for its inverse is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 being a 
\series bold
local isomorphism 
\series default
(i.e.
 each point in its source has an open neighborhood carried diffeomorphically
 onto an open neighborhood in the target).
 By the Inverse Function Theorem, this is equivalent to the isomorphism
 property for the tangent map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\Sigma(g,h):T_{g}(G)\oplus T_{h}(G)=T_{(g,h)}(G\times G)\to T_{(g,gh)}(G\times G)=T_{g}(G)\oplus T_{gh}(G)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We shall now use left and right translations to reduce this latter 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem to the special case 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h=e$
\end_inset

, and in that special case we will be able to compute the tangent map explicitel
y and see the isomorphism property by inspection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Algebraic Geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout these notes, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 Unless otherwise specified, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be a positive integer.
 In this case, we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 to denote a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 Similarly we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]=K[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 to denote a polynomial ring in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}=T_{1},\dots,T_{n}$
\end_inset

 with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will define 
\series bold
affine algebraic sets
\series default
.
 Before we do this, we first introduce the following notation: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a set of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

 to be the set of common zeros of the polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }f\in\mathcal{P}\}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 is another set of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\subseteq\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
inclusion-reversing
\series default
.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated as an ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})=\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}),
\]

\end_inset

where we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})=\mathrm{V}(\{f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

 since the reverse inclusion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is inclusion-reversing.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}f_{i}\right)(\boldsymbol{x}) & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})\cdot0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}f_{i}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maximal ideals defined by points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\colon K[\boldsymbol{T}]\to K$
\end_inset

 be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}(T_{i})=x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 to be the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}=\{f\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong K$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be another ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 in terms of the maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}\mid\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use this reformulation many times throughout this article.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Zariski Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are almost ready to define algebraic sets, but first we need to prove
 the following lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following relations hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(0)=K^{n}\text{ and }\mathrm{V}(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For two ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 of ideals, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(0)=K^{n}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\not\supseteq\langle1\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subseteq\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 from the inclusion-reversing property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{ab}$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But this follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is very important to pay close attention to what is actually used in
 proofs.
 For example, in the proof of the second statement of this lemma, we only
 used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal (even though it is a maximal ideal).
 This gives us an idea for how we can generalize things.
 In particular, we will be replacing maximal ideals of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 with arbitrary prime ideals.
 Keep this in mind! 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This lemma implies that there is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 for which the closed subsets are exactly those of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 We call this topology the 
\series bold
Zariski topology
\series default
 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 to mean the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the Zariski topology.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
dimensional affine space
\series default
.
 Closed subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
affine algebraic sets
\series default
.
 In particular, note that singletons are closed since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{x}\}=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hilbert's Nullstellensatz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The connection between affine algebraic sets and commutative algebra is
 established by Hilbert's Nullstellensatz:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hilbert's Nullstellensatz) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Jacobson
\series default
, that is, for every prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{p}=\bigcap_{\begin{subarray}{c}
\mathfrak{m}\supset\mathfrak{p}\\
\mathfrak{m}\text{ is maximal}
\end{subarray}}\mathfrak{m}.
\]

\end_inset

Moroever, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We shall not prove this result here since a proof is best left for a course
 in Commutative Algebra (see my Algebra notes for such a proof).
 Instead, we will focus on the consequences of this theorem in regards to
 algebraic geometry.
 First let us consider some consequences when working over the algebraically
 closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

-algebra, thus from the Nullstellenatz, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}\hookrightarrow\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a finite extension of fields; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 by the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\to\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\overline{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal which contains the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}=\langle T_{1}-x_{1},\dots,T_{n}-x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore both are equal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus the proposition tells us that the set of all points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with the set of all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we really do need 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 to be algebraically closed for this to hold.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle T^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]/\langle T^{2}+1\rangle\cong\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle T^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 does not come from a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 doesn't even vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are more maximal ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 than just the ones which correspond to points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (there are more maximals ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 than just those of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}=\langle T-x\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

).
 On the other hand, the Nullstellensatz guarentees that for all maximal
 ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

, we will have either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In the second case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and in the first case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{z,\overline{z}}=\langle(T-z)(T-\overline{z})\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a complex number in the upper-half plane (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Im}(z)>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Correspondence Between Radical Ideals and Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall focus on the consequences of Hilbert's Nullstellensatz when
 working over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily algebraically closed).
 To do this, we introduce the following notation: let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all functions which vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Z)=\{f\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }x\in Z\}.
\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

, thus it is also called the ideal of functions which vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Furthemore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Z)=\bigcap_{x\in Z}\mathfrak{m}_{x}.
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}\subset A\\
\mathfrak{p}\text{ prime ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{p}=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\subset A\\
\mathfrak{m}\text{ maximal ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{m}.
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, the first equality holds in arbitrary commutative rings and the
 second equality follows from Hilbert's Nullstellensatz.
 We shall use this fact to prove the following proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.12}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 be a subset.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{IV}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)=\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}) & =\bigcap_{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})}\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\\
 & =\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\\
\text{maximal ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{m}\\
 & =\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 This is a simple assertion for which we do not need the Nullstellensatz.
 On the one hand we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathrm{VI}(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)\supseteq\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand let 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposition implies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{radical ideals } 
\backslash
mathfrak{a} 
\backslash
text{ of }k[T_1 
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
dots 
\backslash
text{,} T_n ]  
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[r, " V ", shift left = 1] & 
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{closed subsets } Z 
\backslash
text{ of }A  
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[l, " I ", shift left=1] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

are mutually inverse bijections, whose restritions define a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\text{maximal ideals of }k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]\}\longleftrightarrow\{\text{points of }\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms of Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
of affine algebraic sets if there exists polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T_{1},\dots,T_{m}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})\in(k[T_{1},\dots,T_{m}])^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
represents 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\series bold
components 
\series default
of this representation.
 We denote the set of morphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{m}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the defining equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Of particular interest is the case 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbb{A}_{K}^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 simply becomes a scalar 
\series bold
polynomial function
\series default
 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\to V(T_{2}-T_{1}^{2})\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto(x^{2},x)$
\end_inset

, is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 It is even an isomorphism with inverse morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\mapsto y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\to V(T_{2}^{2}-T_{1}^{2}(T_{1}+1))$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto(x^{2}-1,x(x^{2}-1))$
\end_inset

, is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(k)\neq2$
\end_inset

, it is not bijective: 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 are both mapped to the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(k)=2$
\end_inset

, it is bijective but not an isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We identify the space 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\times n)$
\end_inset

-matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n^{2}}(k)$
\end_inset

, thus giving 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the structure of an affine algebraic set.
 Then sending a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 to its determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(A)$
\end_inset

 is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 of affine algebraic sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, consider the exponential function 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{exp}:\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 This is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a morphism of algebraic sets.
 Indeed, this map is not even continuous with respect to the Zariski topology:
 The preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{2\pi in\mid n\in\mathbb{Z}\}$
\end_inset

, which is not closed in the Zariski topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(T_{2}-T_{1}^{2},T_{3}-T_{1}^{3})\subset\mathbb{A}^{3}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=V(T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2})\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 whose components are 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{1}T_{2},T_{1}^{2}T_{2}^{2}+T_{3})$
\end_inset

 is a morphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x_{1}x_{2},x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3})=(y_{1},y_{2})\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 We verify this by showing that the point satisfies the defining equation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2})(y_{1},y_{2}) & =y_{1}-y_{2}-y_{2}^{2}\\
 & =(x_{3}+x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2})-(x_{1}x_{2})-(x_{1}x_{2})^{2}\\
 & =x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}:K[T_{1}',T_{2}']/\langle T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2}\rangle\to K[T_{1},T_{2},T_{3}]/\langle T_{2}-T_{1}^{2},T_{3}-T_{1}^{3}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra map induced by mapping
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T_{1}' & \mapsto T_{1}T_{2}\\
T_{2}' & \mapsto T_{1}^{2}T_{2}^{2}+T_{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(1-T_{1}T_{2})\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\mapsto x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is not an algebraic set.
 This shows that the image of an algebraic set is not necessarily an algebraic
 set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of an affine algebraic set is still not satisfactory.
 We list three problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Open subsets of affine algebraic sets do not carry the structure of an affine
 algebraic set in a natural way.
 In particular, we cannot glue affine algebraic sets along open subsets
 (although this is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural operation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for geometric objects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intersections of affine algebraic sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 are closed and hence again affine algebraic sets.
 But we cannot distinguish between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(X)\cap\mathrm{V}(Y)\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(Y)\cap\mathrm{V}(X^{2}-Y)\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 although the geometric situation seems to be different.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Affine algebraic sets seem not to help in studying solutions of polynomial
 equations in more general rings than algebraically closed fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Morphisms are Zariski-Continuous Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now want to show that morphisms are continuous with respect to the Zariski
 topology.
 We first need a lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaamy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})\cap V(q_{1},\dots,q_{s})=V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r},q_{1},\dots,q_{s}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V(q_{1},\dots,q_{s})$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(Z)=V(p_{1}\circ f,\dots,p_{r}\circ f,q_{1}\circ f,\dots,q_{s}\circ f)
\]

\end_inset

is a closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propxy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Lift 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}|_{X}=f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Choosing a lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to choosing a polynomial representation 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})\in(k[T_{1},\dots,T_{m}])^{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaamy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Therefore its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}|_{X}=f$
\end_inset

 must be continuous also.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}:\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be the projection to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate map (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(y_{1},\dots,y_{i},\dots,y_{n})=y_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}|_{X}$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 Let us show this directly: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{1},\dots,z_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

 are distinct points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 (every closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is just a finite set of points).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{i}|_{X}^{-1}(\{z_{1},\dots,z_{n}\})=X\cap\left(\bigcap_{j=1}^{n}V(\pi_{i}-z_{j})\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus the inverse image a closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Zariski-Continuous Maps are not Necessarily Morphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A continuous map with respect to the Zariski topology does not have to be
 a morphism.
 Indeed, consider the complex conjugation map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}:\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 This map is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 To see why, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 is the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\overline{p}_{1},\dots,\overline{p}_{r})$
\end_inset

, where if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}a_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

 , then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{p}_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}\overline{a}_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 does not have a polynomial representation: the only root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}\neq T^{m}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 galois extension with galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{Gal}(L/K)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot:\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto g\cdot x$
\end_inset

, is Zariski continuous because the inverse image of a closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 is the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(g\cdot p_{1},\dots,g\cdot p_{r})$
\end_inset

, where if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}a_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

 , then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}(g\cdot a_{n_{j}})z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 does not have a polynomial representation: the only root of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot\neq T^{m}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(g\cdot):L[T]\to L[T]$
\end_inset

 (and not an 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

One may wonder why we restrict our morphisms between affine algebraic sets
 in the first place.
 Why do we not consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all Zariski-continuous maps? The point is that the category
 of affine algebraic sets are naturally thought of as being objects in the
 category of locally ringed spaces (we will define what these are later
 on) rather than just in the category of topological spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Affine Algebraic Sets as Reduced Finitely-Generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Algebras
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace.
 Every polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 induces a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 of affine algebraic sets.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

 carries in a natural way the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra with addition and multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)\qquad(fg)(x)=f(x)g(x).
\]

\end_inset

To elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 we associate the corresponding constant functions.
 The homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]\to\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))
\]

\end_inset

is a surjective homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X):=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]\slash\mathrm{I}(X)\cong\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
affine coordinate ring
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 be the natural quotient map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as follows: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x):=\widetilde{f}(x),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is any lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 (that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\widetilde{f})=f$
\end_inset

).
 To see that this is well-defined, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}'$
\end_inset

 be another lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}'=\widetilde{f}+\widetilde{g}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}\in I(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =\widetilde{f}'(x)\\
 & =\widetilde{f}(x)+\widetilde{g}(x)\\
 & =\widetilde{f}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in X$
\end_inset

 we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\{f\in\Gamma(x)\mid f(x)=0\}\subset\Gamma(X).
\]

\end_inset

It is the image of the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{1}-x_{1},\dots,T_{n}-x_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\mathbb{A}^{n}(k))=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 under the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the kernel of the evaluation homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)\to k$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 As the evaluation homorphism is clearly surjective, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal and we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is an ideal, consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\mathfrak{a}):=\{x\in X\mid f(x)=0\text{ for all }f\in\mathfrak{a}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=V(\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a}))\cap X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V(\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a}))\cap X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\pi(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is surjective, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =\pi(\widetilde{f}(x))\\
 & =\pi(0)\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is a lift of some polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $0=f(x)=\widetilde{f}(x)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V(\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a}))$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})\subset X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})\subset V(\pi^{-1}(\mathfrak{a}))\cap X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 are precisely the closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 This topology is again called the 
\series bold
Zariski topology
\series default
.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(f):=\{x\in X\mid f(x)\neq0\}=X\backslash V(f).
\]

\end_inset

These are open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
principal open subsets
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, form a basis of the topology (i.e.
 finite intersections of principal open subsets are again principal open
 subsets and for every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{i}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)\cap D(g)=D(fg)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a union of principal open subsets.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=X\backslash V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 For generators 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 of this ideal we find 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=\bigcap_{i=1}^{n}V(f_{i})$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is a basic open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(D(g))=D(f^{*}g)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set.
 The affine coordinate ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is a reduced finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-alebra.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/I(X)$
\end_inset

, it is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)=\sqrt{I(X)}$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism between affine algebraic sets.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\subset Y$
\end_inset

 is a closed subvariety and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to f(X)$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}h=f^{*}g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f(x))=g(f(x)).$
\end_inset

 Or in other words, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(h-g)(y)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h-g$
\end_inset

 is continuous, we must therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $(h-g)(y)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=g$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is not dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $Z:=\overline{f(X)}$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset Y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)\supset I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I(Z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}g=f^{*}0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
dominant 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalence of Categories Between Affine Algebraic Sets and Reduced Finitely
 Generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Algebras
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(f):\text{Hom}(Y,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))\to\text{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto f^{*}g:=g\circ f$
\end_inset

, defines a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma:\text{(affine algebraic sets)}^{\text{opp}}\to\text{(reduced finitely generated }k\text{-algebras)}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.33}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 induces an equivalence of categories.
 By restriction one obtains an equivalence of categories 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma:\text{(irreducible affine algebraic sets)}^{\text{opp}}\to\text{(integral finitely generated }k\text{-algebras)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A functor induces an equivalence of categories if and only if it is fully
 faithful and essentially surjective.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is fully faithful, i.e.
 that for affine algebraic sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma:\text{Hom}(X,Y)\to\text{Hom}(\Gamma(Y),\Gamma(X))$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 We define an inverse map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is given, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 that makes the following diagram commutative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} k[T_1 '
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
dots 
\backslash
text{,} T_m '] 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi } "] 
\backslash
arrow[d] & k[T_1 
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
dots 
\backslash
text{,} T_n ] 
\backslash
arrow[d] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
Gamma (Y) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] & 
\backslash
Gamma (X)  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

We define 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x):=(\widetilde{\varphi}(T_{1}')(x),\dots,\widetilde{\varphi}(T_{n}')(x))
\]

\end_inset

and obtain the desired inverse homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that the functor is essentially surjective, i.e.
 that for every reduced finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 there exists an affine algebraic set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cong\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(\mathfrak{a})\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/I(V(\mathfrak{a}))=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/\mathfrak{a}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 whose components are 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Write the affine coordinate rings of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)=K[T_{1},\dots,T_{m}]/I(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)=K[T_{1}',\dots,T_{n}']/I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)(T_{i}):=T_{i}\circ f=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Gamma(f)(T_{i})(x) & =T_{i}(f(x))\\
 & =T_{i}(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{i}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))\\
 & =f_{i}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the bijective correspondence between points of affine algebraic sets
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, we also have the following description of morphisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f):\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding homomorphism of the affine coordinate rings.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{x})=\mathfrak{m}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $g(f(x))=\Gamma(f)(g)(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)=\text{Hom}(Y,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Affine Algebraic Sets as Spaces with Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now define the notion of a 
\series bold
space with functions
\series default
.
 For us this will be the prototype of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

geometric object
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is a special case of a so-called ringed space on which the notion of
 a scheme will be based on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
space with functions over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a family 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-subalgebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\text{Map}(U,K)$
\end_inset

 for every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are open and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

, then the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U'}\in\text{Map}(U',K)$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=f_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})\to(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of spaces with functions is a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}f:=f\circ g|_{g^{-1}(V)}:g^{-1}(V)\to K$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(g^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly spaces with functions over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 form a category.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a space with functions and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Space with Functions of an Irreducible Affine Algebraic Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 It is endowed with the Zariski topology and we want to define for every
 open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is a domain, and by definition all the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subalgebras of its field of fractions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field of fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X):=\text{Frac}(\Gamma(X))$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
function field 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 as the set of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

, elements of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

, usually do not define functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 because the denominator may have zeros on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, but certainly 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 defines a function 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It might be even defined on a bigger open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as there exist representations of the fraction with different denominators.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will use functions of this kind to make 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into a space with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.38}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 be elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists a non-empty open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 lies in the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})=X$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 lies in the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})=X$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 the localization of the affine coordinate ring with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\bigcap_{x\in U}\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}\subset K(X).
\]

\end_inset

The localization 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 can be described in this situation as the union 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}=\bigcup_{f\in\Gamma(X)\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}}\Gamma(X)_{f}\subset K(X).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in\Gamma(X)\text{ and }g(x)\neq0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It may be tempting to think that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in\Gamma(X)\text{ and }g(x)\neq0\text{ for all }x\in U\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

but this is not necessarily the case.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{4}$
\end_inset

 be the variety defined by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}T_{4}=T_{2}T_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}/T_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(T_{2}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}/T_{4}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(T_{4}))$
\end_inset

 and by the equation of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, these two functions coincide where they are both defined; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{T_{1}}{T_{2}}|{}_{D(T_{2}T_{4})}=\frac{T_{3}}{T_{4}}|{}_{D(T_{2}T_{4})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So this gives rise to a regular function on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(T_{2})\cup D(T_{4})$
\end_inset

.
 But there is no representation of this function as a quotient of two polynomial
s in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4}]$
\end_inset

 that works on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{2})\cup D(x_{4})$
\end_inset

; we have to use different representations at different points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, it is true that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in\Gamma(X)\text{ and }g(x)\neq0\text{ for all }x\in U\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{D(g_{1})}=\frac{f_{1}}{g_{1}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 share no common factors.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not a constant, then there exists another point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(y)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X,y}$
\end_inset

, we must be able to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{D(g_{2})}=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}|{}_{D(g_{1}g_{2})}=f=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}}|{}_{D(g_{1}g_{2})}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 But the only way we can have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 is if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=hf_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}=hf_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in k[T_{1},T_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is related to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle g_{1},g_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 has depth 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(y)=h(y)f_{2}(y)=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To consider 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 as a space with functions, we first have to explain how to identify elements
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to k$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, the element 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is by definition in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 and we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g/h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and we may set 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):=g(x)/h(x)\in k$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is well defined and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.38})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies that this construction defines an injective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\to\text{Map}(U,k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are open subsets we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

 by definition and this inclusion corresponds via the identification with
 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to k$
\end_inset

 resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to k$
\end_inset

 to the restriction of functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions, we still have to show that we may glue functions
 together.
 But this follows immediately from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 as subsets of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
space of functions associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Functions on principal open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 can be explicitely described as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.40}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be the space with functions associated to the irreducible affine algebraic
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is an equality 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}
\]

\end_inset

(as subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

).
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)=\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 (taking 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}\subset\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

.
 If we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}g=h$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h/f^{n}$
\end_inset

 would show that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we will work with ideals, because our argument will use Nullstellen
satz which is a theorem about ideals.
 So set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{a}=\{q\in\Gamma(X)\mid qg\in\Gamma(X)\}.
\]

\end_inset

Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and we have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\text{rad}\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 By Hilbert's Nullstellensatz we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rad}\mathfrak{a}=I(V(\mathfrak{a}))$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it suffices to show 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(f)$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g_{1}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and as 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note that we needed to use Nullstellensatz here.
 In fact, the statement is false if the ground field is not algebraically
 closed, as you can see from the example of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{x^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 that is regular on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, but not polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The proposition shows that we could have defined 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 also in another way, namely by setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}\text{ for }f\in\Gamma(X).
\]

\end_inset

As the 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology, the axiom of gluing implies that at most
 one such space with functions can exist.
 It would remain to show the existence of such a space (i.e.
 that for 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)=D(g)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}=\Gamma(X)_{g}$
\end_inset

 and that gluing of functions is possible).
 This is more or less the same as the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.40})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The way we chose is more comfortable in our situation.
 For affine schemes we will use the other approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an integral finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra we may construct the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponding irreducible affine algebraic set directly without choosing
 generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as the set of maximal ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\mathfrak{a})=\{\mathfrak{m}\subset A\text{ maximal}\mid\mathfrak{m}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 For an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 we finally define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{m}\in U}A_{\mathfrak{m}}\subset\text{Frac}(A).
\]

\end_inset

This defines a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 which coincides the space with functions of the irreducible affine algebraic
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 corresponding in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This approach is the point of departure for the definition of schemes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Functor from the Category of Irreducible Affine Algebraic Sets to the
 Category of Spaces with Functions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 be irreducible affine algebraic sets and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 a map.
 The following assertions are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of spaces with functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(U)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The equivalence of (1) and (2) has already been proved in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.33})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, it is clear that (2) is implied by (3) by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $U=Y$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that (2) implies (3).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 be the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h\mapsto h\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(D(g)) & =\{x\in X\mid f(x)\in D(g)\}\\
 & =\{x\in X\mid g(f(x))\neq0\}\\
 & =D(f^{*}(g)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As the principal open subsets form a basis of the topology, this shows that
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 The homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism of the localizations 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)_{g}\to\Gamma(X)_{f^{*}(g)}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 this is the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}(D(g))\to\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f^{*}(g))),$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\mapsto h\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 This shows the claim if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is principal open.
 As we can obtain functions on arbitrary open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by gluing functions on principal open subsets, this proves (3).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Altogether we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The above construction 
\begin_inset Formula $X\mapsto(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 defines a fully faithful functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{(Irreducible affine algebraic sets)}\mapsto\text{(Spaces with functions over }k\text{)}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that we can embed the category of irreducible affine algebraic
 sets into the category of spaces with functions.
 Of course we do not obtain all spaces with functions in this way.
 We will now define prevarieties as those connected spaces with functions
 that can be glued together from finitely many spaces with functions attached
 to irreducible affine algebraic sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
connected
\series default
, if the underlying topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\series bold
affine variety 
\series default
is a space with functions that is isomorphic to a space with functions associate
d to an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
prevariety 
\series default
is a connected space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 with the property that there exists a finite covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{X\mid U_{i}})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
morphism
\series default
 of prevarieties is a morphism of spaces with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following categories are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The opposed category of finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras without zero divisors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The category of irreducible affine algebraic sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The category of affine varieties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define an 
\series bold
open affine covering of a prevariety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be a family of open subspaces with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 that are affine varieties such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i}U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety.
 The topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian (in particular quasi-compact) and irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first assertion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a finite covering of Noetherian spaces, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 The second assertion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected and has a finite covering of irreducible spaces, which implies
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open Subprevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now able to endow open subsets of affine varieties, and more general
 of prevarieties with the structure of a prevariety.
 Note that in general open subprevarieties of affine varieties are not affine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding principal open subset.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

 be the localization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 be the affine variety corresponding to this integral finitely generated
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),\mathcal{O}_{X\mid D(f)})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic spaces with functions.
 In particular,  
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),\mathcal{O}_{X\mid D(f)})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.40})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 As two affine varieties are isomorphic if and only if their coordinate
 rings are isomorphic, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),\mathcal{O}_{X\mid D(f)})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=I(X)\subseteq k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding radical ideal.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 as a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 and denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}'\subseteq k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $fT_{n+1}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the affine coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)=\Gamma(X)_{f}\cong k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]/\mathfrak{a}'$
\end_inset

, and we can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a}')\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 to the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinates induces a bijective map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j:Y=\{(x,x_{n+1})\in X\times\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\mid x_{n+1}f(x)=1\}\to D(f)=\{x\in X\mid f(x)\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of spaces with functions.
 As a restriction of a continuous map, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 It is also open, because for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{g}{f^{N}}\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j\left(D\left(\frac{g}{f^{N}}\right)\right)=j(D(gf))=D(gf).
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(fg))\to\Gamma(Y)_{g}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mapsto s\circ j$
\end_inset

, is an isomorphism.
 But we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(fg))=\Gamma(X)_{fg}=\Gamma(Y)_{g}
\]

\end_inset

and this identification corresponds to the composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X\mid U})$
\end_inset

 is prevariety and the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $U\hookrightarrow X$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is connected.
 The previous lemma shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be covered by open affine subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Thus a finite covering suffices.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Function Field of a Prevariety
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are non-empty open affine subvarieties, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and non-empty.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V)\subseteq K(U)$
\end_inset

 by the definition of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Frac}(\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V))=K(U)$
\end_inset

.
 The same argument for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U)=K(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the function field of a non-empty open affine subvariety 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and we denote it by 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
function field 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine varieties.
 As the corresponding homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 between the affine coordinate rings is not injective in general, it does
 not induce a homomorphism of function fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K(Y)\to K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 is not functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties whose image contains a non-empty open (and
 hence dense) subset, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(Y)\to K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Such morphisms will be called 
\series bold
dominant
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.54}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 a non-empty open subset.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subalgebra of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 is another open subset, the restriction map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)\to\mathcal{O}(U')$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of subalgebras of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary open subsets, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cup V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\cap\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then its vanishing set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(0)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 is closed because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Therefore if the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 is zero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is zero because 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that restriction maps are injective.
 The axiom of gluing implies therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cup V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\cap\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

 for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closed Subprevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 We want to define on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 the structure of a prevariety.
 For this we have to define functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 We define: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{Z}'(U)=\{f\in\text{Map}(U,k)\mid\text{for all }x\in U\text{, there exists }V\subseteq U\text{ open and }g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)\text{ such that }f\mid_{U\cap V}=g\mid_{U\cap V}\}.
\]

\end_inset

The definition shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}'=\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Once we have shown the following lemma, we will always write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 (instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'$
\end_inset

 is the sheafification of the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X\mid Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.55}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 Then the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})$
\end_inset

 associated to the affine algebraic set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and the above defined space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

 coincide.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In both case 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is endowed with the topology induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to X$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of affine algebraic sets it induces a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\to(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{Z}(U)$
\end_inset

 for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{Z}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\Gamma(Z)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(h)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 .
 The restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{D(h)}\in\mathcal{O}_{Z}(D(h))=\Gamma(Z)_{h}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g/h^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 We lift 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $V:=D(\widetilde{h})\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}^{n}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(\widetilde{h}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{U\cap V}=\frac{\widetilde{g}}{\widetilde{h}^{n}}\mid_{U\cap V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a corollary of the lemme we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.56}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 be the system of functions defined above.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})$
\end_inset

 is a prevariety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The most general way to construct prevarieties is to take some affine varieties
 and patch them together: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be prevarieties, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(U_{1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}\mid_{U_{1}})\to(U_{2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}\mid_{U_{2}})$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism.
 Then we can define a prevariety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 via the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a set, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\cup X_{2}$
\end_inset

 modulo the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a topological space, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the so-called 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 induced by the above equivalence relation, i.e.
 we say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{1}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{2}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a ringed space, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{(s_{1},s_{2})\mid s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }s_{1}=s_{2}\text{ on the overlap (i.e. }f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U\cap U_{2}})=s_{1}\mid_{U\cap U_{1}})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto\frac{1}{t}:=t'$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)\cong k$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(X\cap X_{1})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(X\cap X_{2})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}=b_{m}T'^{m}+b_{m-1}T'^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U_{2}})=b_{m}T{}^{-m}+b_{m-1}T{}^{1-m}+\cdots+b_{0}\mid_{U_{1}}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}\mid_{U_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

The only way this happens is if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=b_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})=(a_{0},a_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)\cong k[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(X\cap X_{1})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(X\cap X_{2})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}=b_{m}T'^{m}+b_{m-1}T'^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U_{2}})=b_{m}T{}^{m}+b_{m-1}T{}^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}\mid_{U_{1}}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}\mid_{U_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

The only way this happens is if 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{4}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{4}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Projective Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By far the most important example of prevarieties are projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and subvarieties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, called (quasi-)projective varieties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homogeneous Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To describe the functions on projective space we start with some remarks
 on homogeneous polynomials.
 Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 To clean our notation in what follows, we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 to denote 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 A monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=X_{0}^{\alpha_{0}}\cdots X_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We also denote 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\cdots,1)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\cdots X_{n}=\boldsymbol{X}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 A point in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We will frequently use this notation whenever context is clear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
homogeneous 
\series default
of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the sum of monomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain with infinitely many elements and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(\lambda\boldsymbol{x})=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})\label{eq:homogeneous}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is obvious, so we will only prove the other direction.
 We will prove the other direction by induction on the number of terms of
 a polynomial.
 For the base case, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f=c\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homogeneous})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous, but we still need to show that it has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many elements and since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathrm{D}(\boldsymbol{X}^{1})\cap\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 By clearing the denominators of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{a})=f(\lambda\boldsymbol{a})=\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\neq0$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{d}=\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=d-|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{r}-1$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (in fact every nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a solution).
 This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{r}-1$
\end_inset

 can have at most 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=d$
\end_inset

; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For the induction step, assume that we have proven the statement for all
 polynomials with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 terms, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial with 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 terms such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homogeneous})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=c\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}+g,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\nmid g$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in K^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be a point such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that such a point exists since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(g)\cap\mathrm{V}(\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, otherwise we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(g)\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\mid g$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 By clearing the denominators if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{a})=f(\lambda\boldsymbol{a})=\lambda^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset

Arguing as before, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=d$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(\lambda\boldsymbol{x}) & =f(\lambda\boldsymbol{x})-c(\lambda\boldsymbol{X})^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}(f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})\\
 & =\lambda^{d}g(\boldsymbol{x}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus by induction, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must be homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The zero polynomial is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of all homogeneous polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 As we can decompose uniquely every polynomial into its homogeneous parts,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R[\boldsymbol{X}]=\bigoplus_{n\geq0}R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we proceed further, let us introduce some more notation to keep everythin
g clean.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{i}=(X_{0},\dots\widehat{X}_{i},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We also denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{T}]_{\leq d}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg f\leq d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 There is a bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{i}=\Phi_{i}^{(d)}:R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}\to R[\widehat{\boldsymbol{T}}_{i}]_{\leq d}
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f(T_{0},\dots,1,\dots,T_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We construct an inverse map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in the right hand side set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\sum_{j=0}^{d}g_{j}$
\end_inset

 be its decomposition into homogeneous parts (with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=0,\dots,i-1,i+1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{i}(g)=\sum_{j=0}^{d}X_{i}^{d-j}g_{j}(X_{0},\dots,\widehat{X}_{i},\dots,X_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are inverse to each other (as both maps are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear, it suffices to check this on monomials).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{0},X_{1},X_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Psi_{1}(\Phi_{1}(X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}^{3}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2})) & =\Psi_{1}(T_{0}^{2}T_{2}+1+T_{2}^{2})\\
 & =X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}^{3}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
dehomogenization
\series default
, and the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
homogenization 
\series default
(with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{e}$
\end_inset

, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $fg$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d+e$
\end_inset

 and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{i}^{(d)}(f)\Phi_{i}^{(e)}(g)=\Phi_{i}^{(d+e)}(fg).\label{eq:dehomoggraded}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, we will extend homogenization and dehomogenization to fields
 of fractions as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X_{0},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset

 that consists of those elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous polynomials of the same degree.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomoggraded})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have a well defined isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-extensions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{i}:\mathcal{F}\to K(\widehat{\boldsymbol{T}}_{i}),\label{eq:dehomogiso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\mapsto\Phi_{i}(f)/\Phi_{i}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 Often, we will identify 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\widehat{\boldsymbol{T}}_{i})$
\end_inset

 with the subring 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X}/X_{i})=K\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

.
 Via this identification, the isomorphism 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can also be described as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}=f/X_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}=g/X_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f},\widetilde{g}\in K\left[\boldsymbol{X}/X_{i}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}(f/g)=\widetilde{f}/\widetilde{g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{T_{2}^{3}+T_{0}^{2}}\in K(T_{0},T_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{X_{1}^{3}}{X_{2}^{3}+X_{1}X_{0}^{2}}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is its homogenization.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of the Projective Space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is an extremely important prevariety within algebraic geometry.
 Many prevarieties of interest are subprevarieties of the projective space.
 Moreover, the projective space is the correct environment for projective
 geometry which remedies the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

defect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of affine geometry of missing points at infinity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

As a set, we define for every field 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily algebraically closed) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}^{n}(k):=\{\text{lines through the origin in }k^{n+1}\}=(k^{n+1}\backslash\{0\})/k^{\times}.
\]

\end_inset

Here a line through the origin is per definition a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subspace and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(k^{n+1}\backslash\{0\})/k^{\times}$
\end_inset

 the set of equivalence classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})\sim(x_{0}',\dots,x_{n}')\text{ if and only if there exists }\lambda\in k^{\times}\text{ such that }x_{i}=\lambda x_{i}'\text{ for all }0\leq i\leq n.
\]

\end_inset

The equivalence class of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]=[x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 We call the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
homogeneous coordinates 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a prevariety we will assume from now on that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed.
 The following observation is essential: For 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}:=\{[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\mid x_{i}\neq0\}\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k).
\]

\end_inset

This subset is well-defined and the union of the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 There are bijections
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k),\qquad[\boldsymbol{x}]=(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{i}},\cdots\frac{\widehat{x}_{i}}{x_{i}},\cdots,\frac{x_{n}}{x_{i}}\right)=\widehat{\boldsymbol{x}}_{i}/x_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Via this bijection we will endown 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a space with functions, isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{A}^{n}(k),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)}),$
\end_inset

 which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}})$
\end_inset

.
 We want to define on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the structure of a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 becomes an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}}=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}U_{i}=\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, there's at most one way to do this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 by calling a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 open if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This defines a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 as for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}=\mathrm{D}(T_{j})\subseteq U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open (we use here on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 With this definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in\{0,\dots,n\}}$
\end_inset

 becomes an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We still have to define functions on open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 For this, we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)=\{f\in\text{Map}(U,k)\mid f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})\text{ for all }i=0,\dots,n\}.
\]

\end_inset

It is clear that this defines the structure of a space with functions on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, although we still have to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}}=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the following description of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)$
\end_inset

 using the inverse isomorphism of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $k(T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(X_{0},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.59}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be open.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)=\{f:U\to k & \mid\forall x\in U,\text{ }\exists x\in V\subseteq U\text{ open and }g,h\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]\\
 & \text{ homogeneous of same degree such that }h(v)\neq0\text{ and }f(v)=g(v)/h(v)\text{ }\text{for all }v\in V\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has locally the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in k[T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the inverse of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields the desired form of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be an element of the right hand side.
 We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus locally on 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g/h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Once more applying the isomorphism 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has locally the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in k[T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{U\cap U_{1}}=\frac{T_{2}^{2}+1}{T_{0}+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Then the inverse of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{X_{2}^{2}+X_{1}^{2}}{X_{0}^{2}+X_{1}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 The bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}})\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k).
\]

\end_inset

of spaces with functions.
 The space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)})$
\end_inset

 is a prevariety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first assertion follows from the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.59})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions that has a finite open covering by affine varieties.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible since it is connected and is covered by finitely many irreducibl
e open subsets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is by its very definition the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U_{i})=k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, we usually describe 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

 as the field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=\{f/g\mid f,g\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]\text{ homogeneous of the same degree}\}.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i,j\leq n$
\end_inset

 the identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U_{i})\cong K(U_{j})$
\end_inset

 is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}\circ\Phi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be described explicitely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(U_{i})=k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right)\mapsto k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{j}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{j}}\right)=K(U_{j}),\qquad\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{i}}\mapsto\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{i}}\frac{X_{i}}{X_{j}}=\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{j}}.
\]

\end_inset

We use these explicit descriptions to prove the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.61}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The only global functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 are the constant functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=k$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is not an affine variety for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.54})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=\bigcap_{0\leq i\leq n}\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U_{i})=\bigcap_{0\leq i\leq n}k\left[\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right]=k,
\]

\end_inset

where the intersection is taken in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 The last assertion follows because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 were affine, its set of points would be in bijection to the set of maximal
 ideals in the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 consists of only one point, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gluing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 to Make 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now want to describe how we can glue 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 to make 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 in explicit detail.
 First we start with the rings 
\begin_inset Formula $k[S]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the homogeneous coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $T:=\frac{X_{1}}{X_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:=\frac{X_{0}}{X_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Projective Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A prevariety is called a 
\series bold
projective variety 
\series default
if it is isomorphic to a closed subprevariety of a projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

As in the affine case, we speak of projective varieties rather than prevarieties.
 Similarly, we will talk about subvarieties of projective space, instead
 of subprevarieties.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in k[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $f([\boldsymbol{x}])$
\end_inset

 obviously depends on the choice of the representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 and we cannot consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous, at least the question whether the value is zero or nonzero
 is independent of the choice of a representative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}=f_{1},\dots,f_{m}$
\end_inset

 be a finite collection of homogeneous polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}_{+}(\boldsymbol{f})=\{[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\mid f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }i=1,\dots,m\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})=\{(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n})\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\mid f_{i}(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n})=0\text{ for all }i=1,\dots,m\}.
\]

\end_inset

Subsets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

 are closed.
 More precisely we have 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})\cap U_{i}=V(\Phi_{i}(f_{1}),\dots,\Phi_{i}(f_{m})),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes as usual dehomogenization with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We will see that all closed subsets of the projective space are of this
 form.
 To do this we consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\qquad(x_{0},\cdots,x_{n})\mapsto(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

As for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{f^{-1}(U_{i})}:f^{-1}(U_{i})\to U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties, this holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C(Z)$
\end_inset

 its closure in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 Affine algebraic sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
affine cones 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda x\in X$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in k^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C(Z)$
\end_inset

 is an affine cone in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 It is called the 
\series bold
affine cone of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following assertions are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an affine cone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is generated by homogeneous polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists a closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=C(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is generated by homogeneous polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Segre Embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{0},\dots,Y_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to find an easy description of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)=\mathbb{P}^{(n+1)(m+1)-1}$
\end_inset

 be projective space with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 There is an obviously well-defined set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}=x_{i}y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmasegreembedding}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 be the set-theoretic map as above.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The image 
\begin_inset Formula $X=f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 is a projective variety in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

, with ideal generated by the homogeneous polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}Z_{i',j'}-Z_{i,j'}Z_{i',j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i,i'\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j,j'\leq m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to X$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a projective variety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 are exactly those subsets that can be written as the zero locus of polynomials
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n},Y_{0},\dots,Y_{m}]$
\end_inset

 that are bihomogeneous in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is obvious that the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 satisfy the given equations.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the given equations.
 At least one of these coordinates must be non-zero; we can assume without
 loss of generality that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us pass to affine coordinates by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}=z_{i,0}z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

; so by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

 we obtain a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 that is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuing the above notation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 be a point with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=z$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 are only determined up to a common scalar.
 But then it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 The same calculation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are given (locally in affine coordinates) by polynomial maps; so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It follows by the isomorphism of (2) that any closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the zero locus of homogeneous polynomials in the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 of bihomogeneous polynomials in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 (of the same degree).
 Conversely, a zero locus of bihomogeneous polynomials can always be reweritten
 as a zero locus of bihomogeneous polynomials of the same degree in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 But such a polynomial is obviously a polynomial in the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, so it determines an algebraic set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cong\mathbb{P}^{n}\times\mathbb{P}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

.
 Then Segre embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{2}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{5}(k)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left([x_{0}:x_{1}],[y_{0}:y_{1}:y_{2}]\right)\mapsto[x_{0}y_{0}:x_{0}y_{1}:x_{0}y_{2}:x_{1}y_{0}:x_{1}y_{1}:x_{1}y_{2}]:=[z_{00}:z_{01}:z_{02}:z_{10}:z_{11}:z_{12}].
\]

\end_inset

By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasegreembedding})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the vanishing ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{2}(k))$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle Z_{00}Z_{11}-Z_{01}Z_{10},Z_{00}Z_{12}-Z_{02}Z_{10},Z_{01}Z_{12}-Z_{02}Z_{11}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

We can view this as the ideal generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 minors of the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}Z_{00} & Z_{01} & Z_{02}\\
Z_{10} & Z_{11} & Z_{12}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

This is an example of a 
\series bold
determinantal variety
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 as a topological space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the following basic definition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Spec}\,A:=\left\{ \mathfrak{p}\subset A\mid\mathfrak{p}\text{ is a prime ideal}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

We will now endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a topological space.
 For every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which do not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\{f\})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\{f\})$
\end_inset

 in order to simplify notation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\mapsto V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 is an inclusion reversing map from the set of ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to the set of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the following relations hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $V(0)=\text{Spec }A\text{ and }V(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For two ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})=V(\mathfrak{ab})=V(\mathfrak{a})\cup V(\mathfrak{b}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{a}_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of ideals, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=V\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}V(\mathfrak{a}_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subset\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subset\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subset\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subset\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{ab})\supset V(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})\supset V(\mathfrak{a})\cup V(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{ab})\subset V(\mathfrak{a})\cup V(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{ab}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supset\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supset\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 for some prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in\mathfrak{ab}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
That 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=V\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}V(\mathfrak{a}_{i})$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lemma shows that the subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 form the closed sets of a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 This leads us to the following definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 of all prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with the topology whose closed sets are the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 runs through the set of ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, is called the 
\series bold
prime spectrum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 or simply the 
\series bold
spectrum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The topology thus defined is called the 
\series bold
Zariski topology 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

, we will often write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 when we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=V\left(\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subset\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})\supset V(\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}})$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume, for a contradiction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supset\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in\mathfrak{a}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Y):=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset

We obtain an inclusion reversing map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\mapsto\mathrm{I}(Y)$
\end_inset

 from the set of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 to the set of ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(\emptyset)=A$
\end_inset

.
 The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}$
\end_inset

 are all related  as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2.3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathrm{I}(Y)}=\mathrm{I}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{IV}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Y)=\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{DI}(Y)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The maps 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{ideals } 
\backslash
mathfrak{a} 
\backslash
text{ of } A 
\backslash
text{ with } 
\backslash
mathfrak{a}=
\backslash
text{rad}(
\backslash
mathfrak{a}) 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[r, " V ", shift left = 1] & 
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{closed subsets } Y 
\backslash
text{ of } 
\backslash
text{Spec }A 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[l, " I", shift left=1] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are mutually inverse bijections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

.
 This certainly holds for prime ideals and therefore for arbitrary intersections
 of prime ideals as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 This follows from the fact that the radical of an ideal equals the intersection
 of all prime ideals containing it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\supseteq Y & \iff\mathrm{I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\mathrm{V}(\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}})\supseteq\mathrm{V}\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\supseteq\mathrm{V}\mathrm{I}(Y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Y)$
\end_inset

 is the smallest closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and assume (to obtain a contradiction) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

, there exists a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\sqrt{0}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}.$
\end_inset

 In particular, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\supseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belongs to every prime ideal which does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

) and assume (to obtain a contradiction) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\notin\sqrt{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (ax)^{n}\right\} _{n\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 forms a multiplicative set, and so we can localize at 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ax}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=\iota_{ax}^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{ax}\colon A\to A_{ax}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (if it did, then it'd certainly contain 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

).
 This is a contradiction.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\supseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{DI}(Y) & =\mathrm{D}\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathfrak{p}\right)\\
 & =\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{p})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 This follows from part 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(\mathfrak{a}):=\text{Spec}(A)\backslash V(\mathfrak{a}).
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then we write 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\rangle)$
\end_inset

.
 Open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
principal open sets 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(0)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(u)=\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 for any unit 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in A$
\end_inset

.
 As for a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $fg\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(f)\cap D(g)=D(fg).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 be a family of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)\subseteq\bigcup_{i}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{n}$
\end_inset

 is contained in the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)\subseteq\bigcup_{i}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $V(g)\supseteq V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Applying this to 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f_{i}))_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}A$
\end_inset

 if and only if the ideal generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 The principal open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

 the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 are quasi-compact.
 In particular, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec}A$
\end_inset

 is the intersection of closed sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)$
\end_inset

.
 By taking complements we see that the 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 form a basis for the topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a family of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)\subseteq\bigcup_{i\in I}D(g_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}=\sum_{i\in I}a_{i}g_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\notin J$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subseteq I$
\end_inset

 a suitable finite subset.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)\subseteq\bigcup_{j\in J}D(g_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact by the first part of the proposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact if and only if it is the complement of a closed set of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U=D(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=D(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})=D(f_{1})\cup\cdots\cup D(f_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a finite union of compact spaces, it must be compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D(g)\}_{g\in A}$
\end_inset

 forms a basis for the topology, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\bigcup_{i\in I}D(g_{i})
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D(g_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, there exists a finite subcovering, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{D(g_{1}),\dots,D(g_{n})\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}D(g_{i})=D(g_{1},\dots,g_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

In particular, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=D(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle x^{2},y^{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}=\langle x^{2},xy,y^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subset\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 (where the inclusion is strict), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=V(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=I(Y)$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $fg\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\subseteq V(fg)=V(f)\cup V(g).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is irreducbile, either 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq V(f)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq V(g)$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 Then by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{Y}=V(\mathfrak{p})=V(I(\{\mathfrak{p}\})=\overline{\{\mathfrak{p}\}}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 is the closure of the irreducible set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

 and therefore irreducible.
 This implies that the dense subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is also irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that for arbitrary irreducible subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 the prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Y)$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 But this is clearly true if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is closed, or more generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is locally closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\mapsto V(\mathfrak{p})=\overline{\{\mathfrak{p}\}}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 onto the set of closed irreducible subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 Via this bijection, the minimal prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 correspond to the irreducible components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn2.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
closed 
\series default
if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

 is closed,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say that a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
generic point 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\{\eta\}}=X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 be two points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
generization 
\series default
or that 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
specialization 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in\overline{\{x\}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
maximal point 
\series default
if its closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\{x\}}$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is generic if and only if it is a generization of every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As the closure of an irreducible set is again irreducible, the existence
 of a generic point implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 is the spectrum of a ring, the notions introduced in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defn2.8})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 have the following algebraic meaning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is closed if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is a generic point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimal prime ideal.
 This exists if and only if the nilradical of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a generization of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is a specialization of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{x'}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is a maximal point if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a minimal prime ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 defines a contravariant functor from the category of rings to the category
 of topological spaces.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism of rings.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of.
 Therefore we obtain a map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi=\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathrm{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathfrak{q})=\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{V}(S))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi(S))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))=\overline{^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:dom"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 A prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(S)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))} & =\mathrm{VI}(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})))\\
 & =\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})}\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})\right)\\
 & =\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}))\\
 & =\mathrm{V}\left(\sqrt{\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b})}\right)\\
 & =\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The proposition shows in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}(\psi\circ\varphi)=^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi\circ^{\mathrm{a}}\psi$
\end_inset

 for any ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon B\to C$
\end_inset

, we obtain a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 from the category of rings to the category of topological spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is dominant (i.e.
 its image is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

) if and only if every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We apply 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dom})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2.12}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a surjective homomorphism of rings with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }B$
\end_inset

 onto the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicative subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to S^{-1}A=:B$
\end_inset

 be the canonical homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }S^{-1}A$
\end_inset

 onto the subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 consisting of prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S\cap\mathfrak{p}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In both cases it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective with the stated image.
 Moreover in both cases a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 contains an indeal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi(V(\mathfrak{b}))=V(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))\cap\text{Im}(^{a}\varphi)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p},\mathfrak{q}\subset A$
\end_inset

 be prime ideals.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows that the passage from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 cuts out all prime ideals except those contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The passage from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A/\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 cuts out all prime ideals except those containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 localizing with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and taking the quotient modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 (in either order as these operations commute) we obtain a ring whose prime
 ideals are those prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that lie between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa(\mathfrak{p}):=A_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}=\mathrm{Frac}(A\slash\mathfrak{p}),
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\series bold
residue field 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectrum of a Ring as a Locally Ringed Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We will now endow the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a locally ringed space and obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 from the category of rings to the category of locally ringed spaces which
 we will show to be fully faithful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Structure Sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that the principal open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We will define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on this basis and then prove that the sheaf axioms are satisfied.
 The basic idea is this: looking back at the analogy with prevarieties,
 we certainly want to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)=A$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

, we consider the localization 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{f}:A\to A_{f}$
\end_inset

 the canonical ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto a/1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\iota_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{f}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 So it seems reasonable to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))=A_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us check that this is a sensible definition: we must check that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}=A_{g}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

, define restriction maps, and check that the sheaf axioms are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\in\langle g\rangle$
\end_inset

 or, equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $g/1\in(A_{f})^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we obtain a unique ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\colon A_{g}\to A_{f}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\circ\iota_{g}=\iota_{f}$
\end_inset

 by the universal mapping property of localization.
 Whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(g)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(h)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\circ\rho_{g,h}=\rho_{f,h}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, which we use to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we can define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f)):=A_{f}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and obtain a presheaf of rings on the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathrm{D}(f)\mid f\in A\}$
\end_inset

 for the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 The restriction maps are the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the sheaf of rings on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 again by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 For all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X=\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X,x}=\lim_{\mathrm{D}(f)\ni x}\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))=\lim_{f\notin\mathfrak{p}_{x}}A_{f}=A_{\mathfrak{p}_{x}}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a locally ringed space.
 We will often simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 instaed of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{Spec}\,A,\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,A})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 be a principal open set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have to show the following two properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f_{i}))$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i}f_{j})}=s_{j}|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i}f_{j})}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Restricting the presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=X$
\end_inset

 to ease the notation.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{D}(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle=A$
\end_inset

 (indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=A$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=A$
\end_inset

).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f_{i})=\mathrm{D}(f_{i}^{n})$
\end_inset

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 there exists elements 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\in I}b_{i}f_{i}^{n}=1.\label{eq:2.10.3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of 1: let 
\begin_inset Formula $s=a\in A$
\end_inset

 be such that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is zero for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite, there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

, independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{n}a=0$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:2.10.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\left(\sum_{i\in I}b_{i}f_{i}^{n}\right)a=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of 2: as 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}=a_{i}/f_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, the images of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}/f_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}/f_{j}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}f_{j}}$
\end_inset

 are equal for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ge1$
\end_inset

 (which again we can choose independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{i}f_{j})^{m}(f_{j}^{n}a_{i}-f_{i}^{n}a_{j})=0.
\]

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{m}a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $n+m$
\end_inset

 (which does not change 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

), we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}^{n}a_{i}=f_{i}^{n}a_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s:=\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}a_{j}\in A,
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the elements in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:2.10.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{i}^{n}s & =f_{i}^{n}\left(\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}a_{j}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}(f_{i}^{n}a_{j})\\
 & =\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}(f_{j}^{n}a_{i})\\
 & =\left(\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}f_{j}^{n}\right)a_{i}\\
 & =a_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have just proved that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\longrightarrow A\longrightarrow\bigoplus_{i\in I}A_{f_{i}}\longrightarrow\bigoplus_{i,j\in I}A_{f_{i}f_{j}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto(\text{Spec }A,\mathcal{O}_{\text{Spec }A})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A locally ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
affine scheme
\series default
, if there exists a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is isomorphism to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\text{Spec }A,\mathcal{O}_{\text{Spec }A})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Schemes
\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
